   <p><li> "Return of the Tax Olympiad," <i>The Wall Street Journal</i>, May 7, 1993.  <p><li>  Alan Reynolds, "Estimates vs. Reality," in <i>Unleashing America's Potential:   A Pro-Growth, Pro-Family Tax System for the 21st Century</i>, Report of the National Commission on Economic Growth and Tax Reform, reprinted in <i>Tax Notes</i>, January 22, 1996.   <p><li> Tax Foundation, <i>Facts and Figures on Government Finance, 1988-1989 Edition</i> (Baltimore, Md.:   Johns Hopkins University Press, 1988).
<p><li>    Bureau of the Census, <i>Historical Statistics of the United States:   Colonial Times to 1970, Part 1</i>, 1976.<p><li>    Christopher Frenze, "The Mellon and Kennedy Tax Cuts:   A Review and Analysis," Staff Study, Joint Economic Committee, June 18, 1982.   <p><li> Council of Economic Advisers, <i>Economic Report of the President, 1996</i>, February 1996. <p><li>   Office of Management and Budget, <i>Budget of the United States Government, Fiscal Year 1997, Historical Tables</i>, 1996.
   <p><li> Bruce Bartlett, "The Case for Ending the Capital Gains Tax," <i>Financial Analysts Journal</i>, May-June 1985. <p><li>   Lawrence B. Lindsey, <i>The Growth Experiment:   How the New Tax Policy Is Transforming the U.S. Economy</i> (New York, N.Y.:   Basic Books, 1990).   <p><li> Bruce Bartlett, "Static Scoring Gets It Wrong," <i>The Wall Street Journal</i>, December 14, 1994. <p><li>   For a thorough discussion of this issue, see <i>Free Market Energy:   The Way to Benefit Consumers</i>, ed. S. Fred Singer (New York, N.Y.:   Universe Books, 1984).<p><li>    Council of Economic Advisers, <i>Economic Report of the President, 1996.</i><p><li>    Lindsey, <i>The Growth Experiment:   How the New Tax Policy Is Transforming the U.S. Economy</i>.<p><li>    Robert Bartley, <i>The Seven Fat Years </i>(New York:   The Free Press, 1992).  <p><li>  The White House, <i>Claim and Response Packet to Most Frequent Supply-Side Claims</i>, July 1996.
 <p><li>   Gary Robbins and Aldona Robbins, "Cooking the Books:   Exposing the Tax and Spend Bias of Government Forecasts," Institute for Policy Innovation <i>Policy Report No. 129</i>, February 1995.   <p><li> Bruce Bartlett, "Premature Ambush of Tax Cut Scorecard," <i>The Washington Times</i>, August 5, 1996.  <p><li>  Taxes on business are an illusion. Even when collected at the corporate level, all taxes ultimately are paid by individuals. When government imposes taxes on a "corporation," the real effect is lower profits for shareholders, lower wages for workers, and higher prices for consumers.
   <p><li> Robbins and Robbins, "Cooking the Books:   Exposing the Tax and Spend Bias of Government Forecasts."  <p><li>  Christopher Frenze, "Capital Gains and the Revenue Estimation Process," <i>Economic Update</i>, Joint Economic Committee, September 1995.  <p><li>  Christopher Frenze, "Massive CBO Errors in Capital Gains Projections," <i>Policy Analysis</i>, Joint Economic Committee, February 1992.
<p><li>    Alvin Rabushka, "Ten Myths About Higher Taxes," <i>Essays in Public Policy</i> (Stanford:   Hoover Institution, 1993).<p><li>    Lucinda Harper and David Wessel, "A Primer:   What Congress Will Face in Debate Over Taxes and Revenue," <i>The Wall Street Journal</i>, December 27, 1994.<p><li>    Staff Paper, <i>Methodology and Issues in the Revenue Estimating Process</i>.<p><li>    U.S. General Accounting Office, <i>Luxury Excise Tax Issues and Estimated Effects</i>, GAO/GGD-92-9, February 1992.
<p><li>    Joint Economic Committee, <i>1992 Annual Report</i>, April 1992. <p><li>   J. D. Foster, "The Prospects for Improving Official Revenue Estimates," Tax Foundation <i>Special Brief</i>, February 1995.  <p><li>  Office of Management and Budget, Mid-Session Review of the Budget, July 16, 1990, and <i>Budget of the United States Government, FY1997, Historical Tables</i>, 1996.   <p><li> U.S. General Accounting Office, <i>1991 Budget Estimates:   What Went Wrong</i>, GAO/OCG-92-1, January 1992.
<p><li>    Paul Gigot, "Oops!  Weren't We Going to Soak the Rich?" <i>The Wall Street Journal</i>, July 9, 1993.<p><li>    He also lifted the cap on the amount of income subject to the Medicare 2.9 percent payroll tax. This means the effective top rate is really 42.5 percent.  <p><li>  Martin Feldstein, "What the '93 Tax Increases Really Did," <i>The Wall Street Journal</i>, October 25, 1995.<p><li>    Congressional Budget Office, <i>Economic and Budget Outlook, Fiscal Years 1997-2006</i>, May 1996.
<p><li>    "Treasury Analysis Finds GOP 'Flat Tax' Too Costly," <i>The Washington Post</i>, October 31, 1994.<p><li>    U.S. Department of the Treasury, "A Preliminary Analysis of a Flat Rate Consumption tax," April 1995.<p><li>    U.S. Department of the Treasury, "An Analysis of the New Armey-Shelby Flat Tax Proposal," January 1996.<p><li>    Letter to Senator Connie Mack from Congressional Budget Office, March 28, 1995.<p><li>    Office of Representative Richard Armey, <i>The Treasury Department Analysis of the Flat Tax</i>, unpublished paper.
