<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Indexicon Review by Ann Cope</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#OOOOFF" VLINK="#663399">

<H1 align=center>Indexicon Review by Ann Cope</h1>
<hr width=80% align=center>

<blockquote>
The following Indexicon review was written by Ann Cope of the
Central Jersey Computer Club.  The Central Jersey Computer Club is comprised of over 1000
professional engineers, archivists, librarians, and indexers.  Because of her
many years of experience as the principle indexer for Lipincott medical books, Ann
Cope's views on indexing are well respected.  Ann gave a presentation of
Indexicon to a couple hundred members of the Central Jersey Computer Club
and the following piece is a summary of that presentation.
</blockquote>

<hr width=80% align=center>
<h2>Presentation Summary of Indexicon</h2>
<b>by Ann Cope</b>
<BR>July 1996
<BR>Reprinted with permission.

<BR>
<P>

I have a love-hate relationship with Indexicon from Iconovex.  As you may
recall from a little over a year ago, I reviewed its version 1.0.  At that
time, I was amazed that a program could do most of what I had done as a
professional indexer.  Unfortunately, it did it much faster, with less user
tedium and at far less cost to the client.  Of course, I said the &quot;
unfortunately&quot; with tongue-in-cheek.  What had been highly paid, highly
skilled work by a small group of intelligent, dedicated professionals, now
was being made possible by just about anyone with a computer and either
WordPerfect for Windows or Microsoft Word.
<P>

Of course, this was not entirely true.  There still had to be a measure of
user intervention, especially when doing a level 6 (highest of the
multi-level in-context) index.  But we were impressed at how intuitive it
was and the degree of mastery with which it did perform.  Its indices were
far more useable than simply a typical computer index-every-word then sort
it index.  In fact, I was not impressed.  I was amazed and became an ardent
supporter of this product - that was MY competition.
<P>

But it had shortcomings, which secretly made me feel better.  After all,
this program still could not do all that I could as a professional indexer.
For example, version 1.0 could not customize its personal lexicon with
compound words.  Hence, you couldn't feed it many names (&quot;Admiral
Richard E. Byrd&quot;) nor pipe in previously made index entries that
contained compound entries on a single line.  This was a major advantage.

<P>

Well I am happy/unhappy with its new version 2.0.  It is faster the version
1 because of its converting some of the user files to program code.  It can
handle multiple lexicons at once or selectively exclude some.  There are two
different methods of modifying or making lexicons that add to the ability to
customize the outputted product.  You can give level of importance ratings
to all entries in a customized list or individualize each, as the case may
require.
<P>

The selections are more accessible.  Searching is more useful and generally
lesser tweaks seem to have enhanced the product across the board.  But the
great advancement seems to be in two areas.  One is crucial and the other
just is plain nice.
<P>

The most crucial advance that really threatens the future of us professional
indexers (thankfully I am close to retirement, so I can use it as a
freelancer and now REALLY enjoy indexing) is the giant leap to being able to
handle compound words in the customized lexicons.  It appears that a
compound string can have up to nine words.  So phrases such as &quot;Little
Bo Peep Pre-School Children Discount Shops&quot; now can be accommodated.
Now our old indices (less the pagination, of course) can be imported
verbatim as my template for subsequent indexing of the following volume in a
journal series.  Great!
<P>

The really nice other significant addition has nothing to do with the
software.  It has to deal with their customer support that only can be
described as customer-centered (what a refreshing change in computerdom).
They now have published documents that explain how we can manipulate
Indexicon or its helper program (e.g., WordPerfect 6.1) to do those things
we need done that require come guidance.  This would include how to use WP's
Master Document feature to compile and index where a document has multiple
parts.  They even have a document to aid compiling a cumulative index,
something we all crave to have made easier.  This parallels the excellence
of their manual that nicely explains with clarity and an absence of cute
siness rather complex topics and procedures.  Such an aspect of their
service alone is worth the support and encouragement.
<P>

A few gigs:  I know most of you didn't want to use WP 6.0.  Well now you
will have to not want to use WP 6.1.  The new version is incompatible with
the earlier WP version.  Fortunately, customized lexicons can be converted
for use under the new Indexicon.
<P>

A major ding still has to deal with how Indexicon handles proper nouns.
Parts of multiple proper nouns, when appearing alone (e.g., &quot;
Eisenhower,&quot; where it does not appear with &quot;Dwight David,&quot;
&quot;President&quot; or &quot;General&quot;), are overlooked by default.
This only can be rectified by importing each to-be overlooked singular
proper noun into a customized lexicon.  But that would require doing manual
macro index, which this program is supposed to obviate.  Why could we not
have the choice of turning on or off this &quot;feature,&quot; that is
locked off by default?
<P>

I just had an index job that had a critical person's name (&quot;Speed&quot;
) appear singularly a number of times in the text that should have been
indexed.  The author tended to use only last names after having introduced
characters.  But all further incidents of Lt. Speed's name were omitted by
Indexicon.  I had to manual redo the index to find every incidence of &quot;
Speed.&quot;
<P>

That would not have been required if I had originally entered &quot;Speed
&quot; as a noun always to be indexed in my customized lexicon.  Sure, there
would have been some entries that required deletion (such as when &quot;
Speed&quot; was used as a non-proper noun at the beginning of a sentence).
But that would have been far better than having to go back through the
document to find each occurrence of the proper noun.
<P>

So it isn't perfect, but my is it better.  And great, even with a few
blemishes that still would be nice to have corrected.  Let's see it in
action (do the demonstration by indexing a 150-page historical manuscript on
contemporary polar history).
<BR><BR><BR>
<center>
<a href="REVIEWS.HTM">Return to Reviews Page</a>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<a
href="../INDEX.HTM">Indexicon HomePage</a>
