<html><head>
<title>Indexicon Review by Jeanie Crain</title>
</head>

<body BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" link="#0000FF" vlink="#663399">

<h1 align=center>Indexicon Review by Jeanie Crain</h1>

<hr align=center width=80%>
<blockquote>
 <b>Beta Tester Survey
Question:</b><i> "Would you recommend Indexicon to other professional
writers? Why or why not?</i>
<p>
<b>Professor Crain:</b><i> "Yes. You will be interested in referencing the
full review I have provided you....."</i><p>
</blockquote>

<hr align=center width=80%>


<h2>Indexicon Review</h2>
<B>by Jeanie C. Crain</b>
<BR>Professor, English
<br>Missouri Western State College
<br>E-mail:  crain@griffon.mwsc.edu
<br>January 1996

<P>
.... Imagine being able to write your document before you begin worrying
about
 what items in it need to be flagged for inclusion in the Index.  Thanks
 to Indexicon, this is now possible.
<p>
 Indexicon (for Microsoft Word) enables automatic indexing:  to accomplish
 this, the program analyzes the document, finding and compiling the
 indexable terms automatically; Indexicon bases its choices on the context
 in which a word is used.  The wonder of the software is that properly
 installed, it appears as the last item under the Tools menu; when the
 document is loaded, the writer merely clicks on Indexicon to pull up a
 dialog box where a choice of options can be made, among these, Creating
 Index where the level of detail to be included allows a range from 1 Most
 Comprehensive to 6 Least Comprehensive. Other options include the index
 automatically, generate index at end of document, and monitor the
 process. In using Indexicon, I've discovered a conference-type paper (15
 pages) with a high level of detail and in the most comprehensive mode can
 be indexed in five to ten minutes; longer manuscripts involve more
 computer time. For a short paper, I  find myself setting the function to
 automatic and taking a coffee break; when I return, I complete finesse
 details and formatting. In minutes, I have a sharp, professional index.

<h3>
 Learning to Index Using Indexicon
</h3>
 The logic of the indexing process used in Indexicon is best seen in its
 own "Contents" and On-line Help.  Once Indexicon is installed, the user
 simply clicks on the submenu "Indexicon" under the main menu "Tools." The
 dialog box then enables a choice among options:  Create Index, Entry
 Editor, Exclusion Zones, LexEdit, About, Help, and Cancel.  Choosing Help
 brings up the Contents "Using Indexicon" :
<p>
 Tools<br>
 Contents<p>
 Using Indexicon<p>
 Main Menu<br>
 Indexing a Document<br>
 Level of Detail<br>
 Comparing Levels of Detail<br>
 Editing Index Entries<br>
 Exclusion Zones<br>
 Indexing  Part of a Document<br>
 Getting the Best Index<br>
 Tips and Troubleshooting<p>

 Getting Help, and thus learning Indexicon, is then as simple as clicking
 on "Indexing a Document" where we find the following information taken
 directly from the manual:<p>


 To use Indexicon's basic indexing features
<ol>
<li> Open the document you want to index.
<li> Choose Tools - Indexicon - Create Index.
<li> In the Create Index dialog box choose the level
 of detail you want your index to include, and the
 format for the page numbers in your index.  You
 can also set other options, mentioned below.
<li> Click on OK.
</ol>
 To demonstrate what an index generated in Indexicon looks like, we can
 actually click now on Indexicon in Tools and choose "Create Index."
 Having done this, we will see another dialog box and will have the
 following options:  Generate index at end of document, Monitor progress,
 Save the update during processing, Level of detail, Page number format,
 and Index.  For now, we will click on the first option to "Generate
 Index," wait a mere minute or so, and see a completed, comprehensive index:
<p><b>
 A<br></b>
 Advanced Indexing, 4<br>
 Another dialog box, 2<p>
<b> B<br></b>
 Best Index, 2<br>
 Bloomington, 1<p>
<b> C<br></b>
 Coffee break, 1<br>
 Compuserve. com, 1<br>
 Computer time, 1<br>
 Contents Tables of Authorities, 4<br>
 Contents Using Indexicon, 2<br>
 CPU, 1<br>
 Create Index, 2<br>
 Create Index dialog box, 2<br>
 Creating Index, 1<br>
 Customer Support, 1<p>
 <b>E</b><br>
 Entry Editor, 2, 3, 4<br>
 Entry Editor permits movement, 4<br>
 Exclusion Zones, 2<p><b>
 G</b><br>
 Generate Index, 3, 5<p><b>

 I</b><br>
 Index Entries, 2<br>
 Index Using Indexicon, 2<br>
 Indexicon;
 learning, 2<br>
 Indexicon looks, 2<br>
 Indexicon Version 2.0, 1<br>
 Indexicon's basic indexing, 2<br>
 Indexing Document, 2<br>
 Indexing Part of Document, 2<p><b>
 L</b><br>
 Least Comprehensive, 1<br>
 Level of Detail, 2, 3<br>
 Levels of Detail, 2<p><b>
 M</b><br>
 Mark Entry dialogue box, 4<br>
 MB RAM, 1<br>
 Monitor progress, 2<p><b>
 O</b><br>
 On-line Help, 2<p><b>
 P</b><br>
 Page number format, 3<p><b>
 S</b><br>
 System Requirements, 1<p><b>
 T</b><br>
 Tables-Mark Entry section, 4<br>
 Techsupp iconovex. com, 1<br>
 Tools menu, 1<br>
 Tools-Indexicon-Create Index, 2<p><b>
 U</b><br>
 Update button needs, 4<p><b>
 W</b><br>
 Windows 3.1, 1<br>
 Windows 6.0, 1<br>
 Word's more indexing program, 4<br>
 Workgroups 3.1, 1<p><b>
 X</b><br>
 Xerxes Ave, 1

<p>
 One has to marvel at this point at the completeness and ease with which
 Indexicon has generated an index.   We could at this point stop and
 become users of Indexicon, but looking closely at the above index, we
 probably would see immediately that we might want to add or change
 entries, remove some or all, add subentries, or change the appearance of
 text.  To accomplish this, we simply go back to our original dialog box
 and click  Entry Editor.
<h3>
 More Advanced Indexing</h3>
 The Entry Editor in Indexicon functions much like the Mark Entry dialogue
 box in the Insert-Index and Tables-Mark Entry section in Word under
 Insert. The familiar Find is used to locate index items; these can then
 be edited in any way the writer chooses.  Subentries can also be created
 for any index entry by simply entering Subentry.  For edits to be written
 to the document, the Update button needs to be clicked.  You may also
 cross reference entries by keyboarding in the "cross reference" box; when
 updated, the generated index will contain a cross reference rather than a
 page number.  It's really very easy to review and customize all index
 entries since the Entry Editor also permits movement from entry to entry
 with the click of  a button, using either ((  for back and  (( for
 forward.  Movement through entries can be monitored easily since all
 entries are machine marked symbols.  The real ease provided by Indexicon
 is, of course, that such markings are made automatically rather than
 manually.  Anyone using Word's  more cumbersome indexing program will
 love Indexicon.<p>

 Just as the index can easily be customized, so can the automatic indexing
 process exclude areas in the text for which no entry is wanted, zones
 such as Contents Tables of Authorities, tables, charts, graphs and so
 forth. Additionally, it is possible to index only part of a document by
 highlighting text and then generating an index.
<p>
 Finally, the best index is probably the one created and maintained for
 specific technical or specialized documents.  Here, the maintenance tool
 LexEdit is used.  LexEdit permits the creation of lexicons (defined as a
 list of words to which indexing value has been added) or the importing of
 text lists created in another text editor or word processor.  You can
 also transport your lexicons as straight text files for use in other
 programs. LexEdit allows for 17 syntax categories for indexing:
 adjective, adverb, geographical names, ing verb, ing verb/adjective, ing
 verb/noun, name acronyms and abbreviations, noun/adjective, past tense
 verb, plural noun, present tense verb, past tense verb/adjective, present
 tense verb/noun, personal names, singular nouns, subject acronyms and
 abbreviations. These indexing values are fairly straightforward and
 self-explanatory and also fairly complete and flexible.
<h3>
 Conclusion
</h3>
 If the purpose of computers and software is to make ordinary routines
 less work intensive, then Indexicon is one of the tools of the moment.
 One has to stack up Indexicon's retail price ($129)against its
 usefulness.  For professional writers of multiple and complex documents,
 Indexicon is a "not to be missed" tool.  It can in minutes make the
 writers look like hours were spent at the computer.  What I like about
 the automatic indexing is that it frees me to do the more important
 matter of generating internal text, knowing that I can worry about
 indexing at the appropriate time--after the document has been created,
 revised, and proofed.   As a tool, Indexicon is functions smoothly within
 Word for Windows; permits choice among only useful functions and
 features; provides clear WYSIWYG documentation on-line that is clear,
 helpful and complete; and strikes a useful tradeoff between automatically
 and edited indexes.  Since I'm a devoted Macintosh user, I can only hope
 that Indexicon will soon be available on this platform, also.
<br>...
