<TITLE>Indexicon Smart Electronics Review</title>
</head>

<body BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" link="#0000FF" vlink="#663399">


<h1 align=center>Smart Electronics Reviews Indexicon</h2>

<hr align=center width=80%>
<H2>Indexicon The Mother of All Indexes</h2>
<B>by Joe Dysart</b>
<br><i>Smart Electronics</i></a>.  December 1994
<br>Reprinted with permission

<p>
After Indexicon catches on, Captain Picard and the crew are probably going
to have to redefine "warp speed". This automatic indexer can index a 100-page
document in one minute -- or polish off an entire year's work of a
professional indexer in one hour.
<p>Talk about your endangered species.
<P>Fifteen years in the making, the software can read a document, locate
significant terms and
phrases, and generate a back-of-the-book-style index, all with the click
of a mouse.
<p>
For any doubters still out there, try this one
on for size: Indexicon has already been used to index the 1,300-page
North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) in 12
minutes.
<p>Plus, Indexicon can go beyond traditional indexing to "disambiguate" language
-- something that ordinarily should not be tried at home.  In essence,
this disambiguation function enables the software to determine when
"lead" is being used to describe a common metal, or to indicate that
followers are being taken in hand.

<p>Designed initially for
use with WordPerfect, the program can be customized within that word
processor to give special emphasis to words and phrases that a user
considers especially important. The result: an index that includes
user-generated entries, as well as those selected by
Indexicon.
<br>
. . .
