<TITLE>Indexicon Info World Review</title>
</head>

<body BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" link="#0000FF" vlink="#663399">

<h1 align=center>Indexicon Info World Review</h1>

<HR width=80% align=center>

<H2>Indexicon takes the pain out of indexing</h2>
<b>October 17, 1994</b>
<br>Reprinted with permission
<p>

Anyone who has ever tried to use Microsoft Corp. Word's
so-called "automatic" index-creation utility will immediately appreciate
Indexicon 1.0.
<P>
Iconovex Corp., which a couple of months ago shipped a
version of its indexing program for WordPerfect for Windows, has just
released a version for Word for Windows 6.0.
<P>
Indexicon's
installation routine places the program on Word's Tools menu for quick
access. And unlike Word's automatic indexing feature, Indexicon
does not require you to first create a separate concordance of index terms
before getting started. All you have to do is call up Indexicon, specify
the level of detail you want (on a scale from 1 to 6), and Indexicon takes
care of the rest.
<p>The program also provides pop-up tools for adding, deleting, or modifying
index terms and for excluding sections of your document from being indexed.
<BR><BR><BR>

