<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Step 2 </TITLE>
<LINK REL="Next" HREF="INDEXED.HTM">
<LINK REL="Previous" HREF="STEP1.HTM"></HEAD>
<BODY background="BLUEBACK.GIF" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000"
LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080">


<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>
<CENTER><B>Step 2&#151;Select Indexing Options</B></CENTER></H1>

<blockquote><P>All you have to do on this screen is click <B>OK</B> and
Indexicon will scan your document for significant terms in the text, mark
those terms with index tags, and generate the index at the end of the
document.  But since you&#146;re here, we might as well tell you about the
<a href="#other">other features</a> available on this screen.
</blockquote>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="STEP2003.GIF" WIDTH = 358 HEIGHT = 372 ALT="Create Index
dialog"></CENTER>

<A NAME="other"></A>

<blockquote>
<P><B><I>Level of Detail</I></B><P ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>This is how comprehensive you want your index to be.  Level 1 is most
comprehensive and it will contain <I>all </I>of the indexable terms in the
document; Level 6 includes the most significant indexable terms.  Levels
2 through 5 represent relative increments in between.

<A NAME="E7E1899"></A>
<P><B><I>Personal Names</I></B><P ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>This option is on by default, meaning Indexicon will index most personal
names and rotate the name around the last name.  When the checkbox is not
marked, Indexicon will suppress those names it recognizes, unless they are
part of a larger proper noun or noun phrase that should be in the index.

<A NAME="E7E1902"></A>
<P><B><I>Geographical Names</I></B><P ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>This option is off by default, meaning that Indexicon will suppress most
geopolitical names (cities, states, and nations) that it recognizes, when they
stand alone, but include topographical names (lakes and mountains) it
recognizes in the index.

<A NAME="E7E1905"></A>
<P><B><I>Lexicons</I></B><P ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>This button opens a dialog where you can activate lexicons you have
created with <a href="LEXEDIT2.HTM">LexEdit</a>.  Values you have assigned to
words in <I>your</I> lexicons will override values for those words in the
primary lexicon; this way you can alter how Indexicon makes its indexing decisions.

<A NAME="E7E1908"></A>
<P><B><I>Unknowns</I></B><P ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>This button opens a dialog where you can instruct Indexicon to create a
list of words it did not recognize during processing.  This list can then be
imported into LexEdit, where you can assign values
and grammatical information to those unrecognized words.
</blockquote>

<BR>

<P><center>
<A HREF="STEP1.HTM"><B><img src="HANDAR3.GIF" alt="Previous Step" border=0>&#160;Previous Step</B></A> &#160;&#160;&#160;<A
HREF="STEP3.HTM"><B>Next Step&#160;<img src="HANDAR4.GIF"
alt="Next Step" border=0></B></A>

<BR><BR>
<HR width=80%>
<BR>
