<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reference Document for Microsoft Word</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#ooooff" vlink="#663399">

<H1><center>Reference Document (RD) Field</H1></center>

<center><B>(Microsoft Word)</B></center>
<P>
The Reference Document (RD) field allows you to indicate which files you
wish to include when you are creating a table of contents, table of
authorities, or an index.
<P>
If you have a number of separate documents that you wish to include into
<EM>one</EM> comprehensive index, you can use the RD field to select which
documents you want in the comprehensive index.  Each of these individual
files must contain index fields (Indexicon must be run on each of them.  For
better results, do not check the Generate Index at end of Document box).
<P>
<H2>How To</h2>
<h3>Use Reference Document (RD) field with Indexicon:</h3>
<P>
<OL>
<LI>Run Indexicon on the series of documents that you wish to create an
index for.  Do not, for efficiency, generate an index at the end of any of
the documents (Do not place a check in the Generate Index at end of Document
box)</li>
<p>
<li>Open the document in which you want the index to appear and scroll to the
end of the document.</li>
<P>
<li>Select <B>Insert--Field </B>from the Word menu at the top.</li>
<P>
<li>Select the <B>Index and Tables </B>from the Categories box and <B>RD</B>
from the Field Names box.</li>
<P>
<li>Modify the <B>RD</B> field by clicking your cursor next to the <B>RD</B>
in the Field Codes text box and typing in the filename of the document you
wish to include.  If you include a path to the filename, you must double all
of the back-slashes in the path (i.e., c:\\winword\\docs\\paper1.doc).
<P>
<b>Note:</b>  The Reference Document field appears in your document as hidden text,
so you will not be able to actually see the field unless you click on the
Show\Hide Paragraph button on the tool bar.
<P>
<li>Since you can only reference one document at a time, you must repeat
steps <B>3-5</B> for <EM>each</EM> document/file that you wish to include in
the comprehensive index.</li>
<P>
<li>Once all of your files have been referenced, make sure that your cursor
is at the very end of the document (after the references) and select <B>
Insert--Index and Tables </B>from the Word menu at the top.</li>
<P>
<li>Choose the <B>Index </B>option (you can change the &quot;style&quot; of
the index in this dialog if you would like) and click <B>OK</B>.</li>
<P>
<li>An index will be generated for all of the documents listed in the <B>RD
</B> field.</li>
</ol>

<P>
<BR>
<h3>Number Pages Continuously with Reference Document</h3>
<P>
You can instruct Word to number your pages continuously in Reference
Document, but you will have to set several options.
<P>
<OL>
<LI>Open the first document that will be indexed (the document that will
begin with page 1) and then choose <B>Insert--Page Numbers</B>.</li>
<P>
<LI>Click <B>Format</B> and in the Page Number Format dialog, make sure that
Page Numbering is set to start at 1.</li>
<P>
<li>Click <B>OK</B> and save your document.</li>
<P>
For <EM>all</EM> remaining documents, you must calculate where page
numbering will begin and then manually set the Page Numbering to start
there.  For example, if the first document is 5 pages long, you must open
the second document and then follow steps <B>1-2</B>, but set the Page
Numbering to begin at 6.  Repeat this process for the remainder of the
documents in the set.
<P>
After all of your page numbering is complete, follow the instructions for
the Reference Document field to include the documents in your index (be sure
to reference the documents in the order that you set in the page numbering).
If you have already generated an index with RD,  make sure that the
documents are referenced in the order that you set the page numbering and
update the index (<B>F9</B>).
</ol>

<BR><P>
<h3>Make each Document a Chapter and Include the Chapter Number in the
Index</h3>
<P>
Like with continuous page numbers, you must manually mark each
document as a chapter and then choose to include it in your index in the
appropriate order.
<P>
<OL>
<LI>Open the first document in the set and type in a desired chapter title
at the top in Heading 1 form.  Now choose <B>Format--Heading Numbering</B>.</li>
<P>
<LI>Choose the chapter style you want and then click <B>Modify</B>.</li>
<p>
<li>At the Modify Heading Numbering dialog, choose what kind of text you want to
appear before the chapter heading, whether you want the chapters to be
bulleted or numbered, what text you want after the chapter heading, and
where to begin the chapter numbering.  (Since we want each document to be a
separate chapter, do not place a check in the Restart Numbering at Each New
Section box).  When you are finished, click <B>OK</B>.</li>
<P>
<LI>Choose <B>Insert--Page Numbers</B>.</li>
<P>
<LI>At the Page Numbers dialog, choose where you want the page numbers to
appear in the Position text box and where you want them aligned in the
Alignment text box.  You can place a check in the Show Number on First Page
box if you wish to display a page number on the first page of a document or
section.</li>
<P>
<LI>When finished, click <B>Format</B>.</li>
<P>
<LI>In the Page Format dialog, place a check in the Include Chapter Number
box and select what heading style to use for the chapter titles (in this
case, heading 1) and what separator you want to use (hyphen, colon, etc.).
Under Page Numbering, select Start at: 1 (since this is the first document
in the set).  When you are finished, click <B>OK</B>.</li>
<p>
<li>Now save the document and then close it.</li>
<P>
<LI>Now open the next document that will be referenced and included in the
index.  Follow steps <B>1-8</B>, but select the appropriate starting chapter
and page number.</li>
<p>
-- In the Modify Heading Numbering dialog, make sure to choose the right
chapter number to start at (Start at 2 for the second document title, Start
at 3 for the third document title, etc.).
<p>
-- In the Page Number Format dialog, make sure that under Page Numbering, you
select the appropriate page that you want the page numbering to begin on
(i.e., if you want continuous page numbering and document one is 5 pages long
and document two is 5 pages long, you should begin page numbering for document
three at 11).  However, if you want page numbers to restart at 1 for each new
chapter/document, you must open each document and set the page numbering to
start at 1.
<p>
<li>After all of your chapter and page numbering is complete, follow the
instructions for the Reference Document field to include the chapter numbers
in your index (be sure to reference the documents in the order that you set
in the chapter and page numbering).  If you have already generated an index
with RD,  make sure that the documents are referenced in the order that you
set the chapter and page numbering and update the index (<B>F9</B>).</li>
<P>
</ol>
<BR><BR>
<Hr>
<BR><center><a href="INDXFAQ.HTM">Return to FAQ</a></center>
<BR>
</BODY>

</HTML>
