<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Master Document for Microsoft Word</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#ooooff" vlink="#663399">

<center><h1>Master Documents</center></h1>
<center></B></I><B>(Microsoft Word)</B><B><I></center>
<P>

</B></I>Some might wish to combine two or more related Word documents in
order to create one comprehensive index.  One of the ways that they can
accomplish this is through Master Documents.  A Master Document is
essentially a container for subdocuments.  Master Document can be used along
with Indexicon to produce a comprehensive index for several documents.
Therefore, when an index is generated, a comprehensive index is considered
for the ENTIRE Master Document (all subdocuments included).
<P>
<h2>How To</h2>

<h3>Insert existing Word documents into a Master Document:</h3>

<P> <OL>
<LI>Open a new document in Word. (<B>File--New</B>) Use the &quot;<B>Normal
</B>&quot; template.<br></li> <p> <LI>Choose <B>View--Master</B>
<B>Document</B>.</li> <p> <li>Type in the &quot;title&quot; of each document
that you wish to include in your Master Document and press <B>Enter</B> after
each one.  For example, if you are including three documents in your Master
Document (one about baseball, one about space, and one about computers), type
in a &quot;title &quot; for each of those documents and press enter after
each one.  These titles can be generic (Baseball, Space, Computers) since
they are only &quot;placeholders&quot; that signify new subdocuments.</li>
<P> -- Word uses built-in heading styles when it creates subdocuments.  Use
these styles when you are entering the &quot;titles&quot; of your
subdocuments. For example, type each <EM>document</EM> title in Heading 1
form and Word will create a new subdocument at every Heading 1. <P>
<LI>Highlight all of the &quot;titles&quot; that you wish to designate as
subdocuments and include in your Master Document.  Click the <B>Create
Subdocument</B> button on the Master Document toolbar.  Make sure that the
first heading selected is the heading level you want Word to use at the
beginning of each subdocument.</li> <p> <LI>Once your Master Document
&quot;template&quot; is finished with all of the headings established, choose
a name for the document and save it. </li> <P> <b>Now you can begin inserting
any subdocuments&#133;..</b> <P> <LI>Position your cursor where you wish to
add an existing document (usually underneath the appropriate subdocument
title).</li> <p> <LI>On the Master Document toolbar, click the <B>Insert
Subdocument</B><I> </I>button.</li> <p> <li>A file chooser will appear where
you can select the document you wish to insert.</li> <P> --You must repeat
steps <B>7-9</B> for <EM>each</EM> subdocument you wish to include. <P>
<LI>You may not actually see the text of the subdocument after you insert
it.  You can open the subdocument <EM>within</EM> the Master Document in two
ways:</li>
<p>
a.) Place the cursor in the subdocument title and click on the Expand button on
the Master Document tool bar (+).<br>
b.) Double-click the Expand button (+) found directly to the left of the
subdocument title.
<P>
<b>Note:</b>  If the text of your document is maximized after you insert it, you
can minimize it by clicking the Collapse button (-).
<P>
<li>To open any subdocument in a different window, you can click the
Subdocument icon at the far left of the subdocument title.</li>
<P>
<LI>Switch to Normal view (<B>View--Normal</B>) and run Indexicon (<B>
Tools--Indexicon</B>) on the Master Document and a comprehensive index will be generated for the entire
document (subdocuments included).
<P>
-- It is important to realize that the page numbers are generated in the
order in which the subdocuments are inserted in the Master Document.
For example, if you first inserted a 10-page document about &quot;
computers&quot; and then inserted a 10-page document on &quot;cars,&quot;
the document related to computers will be numbered from 1-10 (since it was
the first document inserted) and the document related to cars will be
numbered 10-20.  Individual documents are still maintained separately
as well as being in the Master Document.  You can open individual
subdocuments from within the Master Document or from within the
directory the subdocument was originally stored.
</ol>
<BR><P>

<h3>Include Chapter Numbers in the Index with MD</h3>
<P>
In order to have chapter numbers included in the index, you must
first switch to Normal view (<B>View--Normal</B>) and then follow these
instructions:
<P>
<OL>
<LI>Choose <B>Format--Heading Numbering</B>.</li>
<p>
<li>At the Heading Numbering dialog, choose the desired style you want your
chapter titles to appear as and click <B>Modify</B>.</li>
<P>
<li>At the Modify Heading Numbering dialog, choose what kind of text you
want to appear before the chapter heading, whether you want the chapters to
be bulleted or numbered, what text you want after the chapter heading, and
where to begin the chapter numbering.  Placing a check in the Restart
Numbering at Each New Section box will restart chapter numbering at 1 for
each designated section (sections must be divided with a section break).</li>
<P>
<LI>At the Level text box, you are able to assign heading levels to your
chapters.  For example, you choose which heading level you want Word to
designate a new chapter.  If you choose Heading 1 as a chapter style, Word
will assume that each Heading 1 is the start of a new chapter, etc..  For
example, if you want each subdocument to be a new chapter, make sure that
the heading level for your chapter style matches that of your subdocuments.
When you are finished, click <B>OK</B>.
<P>
<LI>Choose <B>Insert--Page Numbers</B>.</LI>
<P>
<LI>At the Page Numbers dialog, choose where you want the page numbers to
appear in the Position text box and where you want them aligned in the
Alignment text box.  You can place a check in the Show Number on First Page
box if you wish to display a page number on the first page of a document or
section.</LI>
<P>
<LI>When finished, click <B>Format</B>.</LI>
<P>
<LI>In the Page Number Format dialogue, place a check in the <B>Include
Chapter Number </B>box and select what heading style to use for the chapter
titles (heading 1, heading 2, etc.) and what separator you want to use
(hyphen, colon, etc.).  Under Page Numbering, you select whether you want
page numbering to begin on the first page or to continue from a previous
section.  You may select any other page if you wish to begin on a page other
than 1.  When finished, click <B>OK</B>.</LI>
<P>
-- This may alter the previous page numbering scheme in your original Master
Document, particularly if you choose to restart numbering at each new
section.
<P>
<LI>If you wish to have page numbers restart at each new section, you must
separate each section with a section break (if you haven't already).  Now
click your cursor into each section and then select <B>Insert--Page Numbers
--Format</B> again and set Page Numbering to start at 1.  You must click <B>
OK</B> each time you set Page Numbering to start at 1 for the changes to
occur.  This must be done for each section in order for page numbers to
restart at every new section.
<P>
<LI>Now run Indexicon on the document.</LI>
<P>
</ol>

<BR><BR>
<Hr>
<BR><center><a href="INDXFAQ.HTM">Return to FAQ</a></center>
<BR>

</BODY>

