Accept-Ranges: bytes
Content-length: 3384
Last-modified: Wednesday, 18-Dec-96 18:54:25 GMT
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Master Documents WordPerfect</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#ooooff" vlink="#663399">

<center><H1>Master Documents</h1></center>
<center><b>(WordPerfect)</center></b>
<p>
A master document is a file that contains links to subdocuments, or other
files. With this feature you can easily organize and more quickly work with
larger documents because you can open and edit portions of the document
rather than the entire document.
<P>
If you are working with a large document you may choose to use WordPerfect's
Master Document feature so you can break up the file into more managable
pieces, perhaps by chapter or section. You can also use this feature create
a comprehensive index for several documents, without having to merge all the
portions of a document into one file.
<P>
<B>To create an index in a master document:</b>
<P>
<OL>
<LI>Open each document that you intend to include in the master document and
run Indexicon separately for each with the Generate Index<B> </B>checkbox
unmarked.</li>
<p>
<LI>Save and close each document when indexing is complete.</li>
<p>
<LI>Open or create a master document.(To create a new master document, open
a new document. Then insert a link to each subdocument by choosing <B>File
</B><B>-- </B><B>Master Document  </B><B>-- </B><B>Subdocument</B> and
selecting the appropriate file).</li>
<p>
<LI>Choose <B>Tools </B><B>--</B><B> Index</B>.</li>
<p>
<LI>In the Index Feature<I> </I>toolbar, click <B>Define</B>.</li>
<p>
<LI>Make any changes to the appearance of the index that you desire, like
the position of the numbers, the page number format, and the index heading
styles. For more information on including chapter numbers in the index, see
<I>Including Chapter Numbers in a WordPerfect Index</I>.</li>
<p>
<LI>Click <B>OK</B>.<br>
&lt;&lt;Index will generate here&gt;&gt; appears at the position of the cursor
in the document.
<p>
<LI>In the toolbar, choose <B>Generate </B>or press <B>Ctrl + F9</B>.</li>
<p>
<LI>Click <B>OK</B>.</li>
<p>
WordPerfect will create an index in the master document that includes all
the index entries from each subdocument. This will also update, if they
exist,<B> </B>the table of contents, table of authorities, lists, and
cross-references in the master document.
</ol>
<P>
<center><H3>Expanding Subdocuments</H3></center>

If you wish to expand your subdocuments into the master document, do so
before generating the index.<B> </B>After expanding the documents, place the
cursor where you want the index to appear and continue with #4 in the
previous instructions.<B> </B>If you leave your subdocument files open when
generating the index in the master document, the subdocuments will be
expanded into the master document during generation, possibly placing the
index at a location other than the end of the document.
<P>

<center><H3>Page Formatting in the Index</H3></center>

WordPerfect will use the same page formatting in the index as defined in the
Page Numbering dialog box. If you are generating an index in a master
document, WordPerfect will, by default, use the same page numbering format,
but will not include chapter numbers. See <I>Including Chapter Numbers in a
WordPerfect Index</I> for instructions on including chapter numbers in the
index.
<P>

<BR><BR>
<Hr>
<BR><center><a href="INDXFAQ.HTM">Return to FAQ</a></center>
