<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chapter Numbers for WordPerfect</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#ooooff" vlink="#663399">

<CENTER><H1>Including Chapter Numbers in the Index</H1></center>
<center><b>(WordPerfect)</center></b>
<P>
If you are creating a large document, you may wish to include chapter in the
index so your readers can quickly and easily find the information they need.
There are two steps you need to perform to ensure you get the type of page
numbering you desire in the index: (1) define the appropriate chapter
numbers in the document or documents, and (2) indicate the page numbering
you want WordPerfect to use in the index.
<P>
<H3>Defining Chapter Numbers in a Document</H3>

In order for WordPerfect to generate an index with chapter numbers, these
chapter numbers must be defined in the document or documents, though the
page numbers themselves need not reflect the chapter numbers.
<P>
<B>To insert chapter numbers into a document:</B>
<P>
<OL>
<LI>Open the document (or subdocument) to which you want to apply chapter
numbering.</LI>
<p>
<LI>Place the cursor at the very beginning of the document or the page where
you want to begin a new chapter. </li>
<p>
<LI>Select <B>Format -- Page -- Numbering</B>.</li>
<p>
<LI>In the Page Numbering dialog, click <B>Value</B>.</li>
<p>
<LI>In the Numbering Value dialog box, indicate the Chapter Number under
Chapter Settings.If you wish, you can also insert the chapter number into
the document by marking Insert and Display at Insertion Point. Keep in mind
that this will insert the page number <I>exactly</I> at the insertion point.</li>
<p>
<LI>Click <B>OK</B>.</li>
<p>
<LI>Click <B>OK</B> to return to your document.</li>
<p>
<LI>Apply chapter numbers in the same manner throughout the document or to
each subdocument you have.</li>
</OL>
<H3>Defining the Page Numbering for the Index</H3>

WordPerfect will, by default, use the same page number formatting in the
index as you applied to your documents. If you are generating an index in a
master document, WordPerfect will, by default, use the same page numbering
format as in the subdocuments, but will not include chapter numbers.
<P>
<B>To change the page type and formatting in the index:</b>
<P>
<OL>
<LI>If you are changing an existing index, place the cursor at the beginning
of the index or somewhere within the index.</li>
<p>
<LI>Choose <B>Tools -- Index</B>.</li>
<p>
<LI>On the Index feature bar, click <B>Define</B>.</li>
<p>
<LI>In the Define Index dialog, click <B>Page Numbering</B>.</li>
<p>
<LI>In the Page Number Format dialog box, you can indicate whether you want
to use the page number format used in the document (or subdocuments) or
define a different format for the index.
<UL>
<LI>By marking Document Page Number Format, WordPerfect will use the page
number format you defined in the Page Numbering dialog box in your document.
If you are generating an index for a master document, WordPerfect will you
use the format defined in each subdocument. You will need to define your
own, user-defined page number format if you want to include chapter numbers.</li>

<LI>Mark User-Defined Page Number Format to specify an different numbering
format for the index. Use the Insert drop down list to insert the page
number codes you want to use in your page numbers. For example, if you want
the chapter number displayed with the page number, you would click Insert
and select Chapter Number. You can type in any other text or you want to
appear with the index page numbers, like a hyphen to separate the chapter
and page numbers.</li>
</UL>
<p>
<LI>Click <B>OK</B>.</li>
<p>
<LI>In the Define Index box, click <B>OK </B>to return to your document.</li>
<p>
<LI>To regenerate your index, place the cursor anywhere in the index and
press <B>Ctrl + F9</B>.</li>
<P>

<BR><BR>
<Hr>
