<html><head><title>Syntactica Web API</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff"><font=+1>




<center><h2>The Syntactica Web API (SWAPI)</h2>
<h3>A Technology Description</h3></center>

<p><center><i>by Terry Maguire<br>
The Iconovex Corporation<br>
June 14, 1996</center></i></p><hr>

<p><ul>
<li><a href="#problem">The Problem: Too Many Words, Not Enough Facts</a>
<li><a href="#technology">SWAPI Technology</a>
<li><a href="#options">SWAPI Options</a>
<li><a href="#enhance">Projected Enhancements</a>
<li><a href="#products">Iconovex Products that Use SWAPI</a>
<li><a href="#advantages">Advantages of the SWAPI Approach</a>
<li><a href="#corporate">About the Corporation</a></ul>
<p>
<hr>


<p>
<a name="problem"><h2>The Problem:  Too Many Words, Not Enough Facts</h2>

<p>The Web is hot.  Carefully designed home pages with bright graphics are hot.  Real-time
multimedia and animated anything are hot.  But as much as we may like the fancy interfaces and
the glitzy toys, the real business of the Web is information exchange, and the vast bulk of that
information is in the form of text.</p>

<p>Which brings us to the problem: the sheer volume of information available on the Web is
overwhelming, and finding the particular fact youre looking for on a particular day can be pretty
frustrating.  You know its probably out there somewhere, but you just cant seem to locate it.  In
short, the information is available, but its not accessible.</p>

<p>For most users the only available solution is the search engine, and this probably works well
enough for casual searches on simple subjects.  If youre casually interested in volcanoes, you
can enter that term in most search engines and get back a list of sites that mention volcanoes,
though of course some of these hits will be only passing references and one might refer to a
midget football league team in Arizona.  But you wont discover that until after youve
downloaded the page that showed up in the search engines hit list as Arizonas Famous
Volcanoes.</p>

<p>The problem here is that most search engines depend on some form of inverted index, a simple
table of words and their locations with no information about context or meaning.  Search engines
find words, not facts.</p>

<p>The solutionwhether youre building a product for the Internet or a corporate Intranet, whether
for the end-user hunting for information or for the Webmaster who wants to make information
more accessible to end-usersis the unique combination of Natural Language Processing and
hypertext-linking technology found in the Syntactica Web API.</p>

<hr width="25%">
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<a name="technology"><h2>SWAPI Technology</h2></a>


<p>SWAPIs consists of three basic functions:  analysis of the text, creation of hypertext links
within that text, and for those who wish to work at the file level rather than the stream level, the
production of hyperlinked output pages.</p>

<ul><li>Natural Language Processing is used to analyze the text and extract significant concepts
from it.  These concepts are used as a basis for producing four different representational
views of the texts principal ideas: a keyword index, a concept index, a full-text summary,
and a table of contents based on headings.
<li>SWAPIs  hypertext technology links the entries in each of these representational views with
their source in the original text.
<li>At the file level, SWAPI builds hyperlinked pages for each of the representational views.
Each of these views can be used to present the end-user with a logical and coherent mode of
hypertext access to the information within the text.</ul>

<p>These three elements of the technology are discussed in detail in the sections that follow.</p>

<center><h3>Natural Language Processing</h3></center>

<p>The Syntactica engine, the linguistic processing technology at the heart of SWAPI, relies
exclusively on Natural Language Processing for textual analysis.  It does not use word frequency
counts or any other form of statistical analysis of textual composition.  Instead, syntactic rules
and semantic weights are used to determine the significant concepts within the text.  Each word
in these concepts is checked against Syntacticas primary lexicon of 130,000+ words and
assigned a preliminary semantic value.  Then the syntax of each concept is analyzed to determine
the relative importance of its constituent elements.  Finally, all this semantic and syntactical
information is combined to determine the overall importance of the concept.</p>

<p>The term nuclear power plants, for instance, would receive roughly twice as much value if it
were the primary subject of a sentence as opposed to a direct object.  It would receive even less
value if it appeared in a subordinated clause, and less still if in some sort of parenthetic
statement.  The following examples illustrate the importance of using this contextual information
when evaluating content.</p>

<p><i><b>As a subject:</b></i><br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Nuclear power plants in the Northeast are responsible for 80% of Canadas acid rain.</p>

<p><i><b>As an object:</b></i><br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Stricter environmental laws regulating radioactive waste have affected nuclear power
plants throughout the U.S.<p>

<p><i><b>As a parenthetic element:</b></i><br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Large-scale public works projects in the Soviet Union, such as dams, airports, and
nuclear power plants, have inevitably been plagued by shoddy workmanship and inferior
materials.</p>

<p>Clearly, the importance of the term nuclear power plants varies considerably with its context.
The Syntactica engine is designed to recognize this contextual difference and to take it into
account when determining which elements in a document are most significant for summarizing
its meaning .  The analysis emphasizes ideas, not isolated words, and this is what most clearly
separates Syntactica processing from the search engine approach.  No matter how complex the
statistical algorithm or how complicated the matrix, inverted indexes are simply lists of words.</p>


<center><h3>Hypertext Linking</h3></center>

<p>By the end of the analysis process, SWAPI has extracted the information it needs to build an
index, a concept index, a summary, and a table of contents for the processed text as well as
locators (primarily byte-offset) that point to the places in the text where the output entries
originated.  In other words, if the first example sentence above caused an index entry Nuclear
power plants to be generated, SWAPI would also have the byte-offset of the first character in
that term and would therefore be able to locate the precise segment of text that generated the
entry.  This information is used to enable the hypertext linkage between the various output
entries and their source locations in the original text.</p>

<p>SWAPI assigns a unique code to each output entry, the final letter of which indicates whether the
entry belongs to the index, concept index, summary, or table of contents.  Using the byte-offset,
SWAPI then writes a fully formatted destination anchor (which includes this code as a name
attribute) in the original text to indicate the location of the term (or concept, etc.) that generated
the entry.  In the above example, the destination anchor might appear as:</p>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;a name=2222222222i&gt;Nuclear power plants in the Northeast are responsible . . .</p>

<p>The corresponding source anchor would appear in the index, and might look like this:</p>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;a href=filename.txt#2222222222i&gt;Nuclear power plants&lt;/a&gt;</p>

<p>All the application engineer needs to do is add the destination filename to the source anchor and
the hypertext link will be complete.  Each entry in the index (or concept index, etc.) will become
a source anchor and will be linked to the location in the original text that generated it.</p>

<p>Depending on the options selected, SWAPI will also generate the source and destination anchors
needed for circular or horizontal linking.  These options are described in detail later in this
document.</p>


<center><h3>Creation of Output Pages</h3></center>

<p>For the application engineer who prefers to work at the file level, SWAPI will create 5 files, one
for each of the primary outputsindex, concept index, summary, and table of contentsand a
fifth file containing a copy of the original text with the destination anchors already inserted.  The
primary output files can be generated as raw data, relying on the application engineer to format
the output as he or she chooses, or they can be generated in preformatted HTML, ready for the
browser.  The following paragraphs describe this preformatted output.</p>

<p><i><b>Index:</b></i>&nbsp;&nbsp;The index is an alphabetized list of key terms hyperlinked to the location where they
occur in the original text.  (In fact, it is a copy of the original text, but this will be transparent to
your end-user.)  At the top of the page is an alphabetical navigation bar which allows the user to
jump to the desired section of the index.  Below the alphabetical bar is another navigational bar
which allows the user to jump to other views (concept index, summary, table of contents) if
you have created these views.</p>

<p>In order to make the index as efficient as possible for the end-user, SWAPI attempts to ensure
that each entry is unique.  Duplicate entries waste the end-users time because while they appear
to be the same in the index, they point to different places in the text.  Four example, an index
might include four entries for tax reform,  potentially confronting the user with a choice such
as:</p>


<a name="here1"></a>
<a href="#here1"><ul>Tax code<br>
Tax reform<br>
Tax reform<br>
Tax reform<br>
Tax reform<br>
Tesla, Nikola<br></ul>
</a>


<p>An end-user interested in the history of tax reform legislation would have to follow each of the
above links and view the original document(s) in order to determine if any of these entries
pertain to the subject.  In order to avoid this situation, SWAPI automatically displays an abstract
of the full phrase for any duplicate entries.</p>

<a name="here2"></a>
<ul><a href="#here2">Tax code</a><br>
Tax reform<br>
<ul><a href="#here2">Tax reform</a> long overdue<br>
Legislature votes on key <a href="#here2">tax reform</a> proposals<br>
Reviewing <a href="#here2">tax reform</a> of the 1980s<br>
Speaker calls <a href="#here2">tax reform</a> smoke and mirrors<br></ul>
<a href="#here2">Tesla, Nikola</a></ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>


<p><b><i>Concept index:</i></b>&nbsp;&nbsp;The concept index is an alphabetized list of key terms, each of which is followed
by an abstract of the phrase in which it occurred.  This allows the end-user to immediately see
the context in which every term is used.  If the above index terms appeared in a concept index, it
might look like the following:</p>

<a name="spoof"></a>
<ul><a href="#spoof">Tax code</a><br>
<ul>Representative Harris offers last-minute amendment to tax code</ul></ul>

<ul><a href="#spoof">Tax reform</a><br>
<ul>Tax reform long overdue</ul></ul>

<ul><a href="#spoof">Tax reform</a><br>
<ul>Legislature votes on key tax reform proposals</ul></ul>

<ul><a href="#spoof">Tax reform</a><br>
<ul>Reviewing tax reform of the 1980s</ul></ul>

<ul><a href="#spoof">Tax reform</a><br>
<ul>Speaker calls tax reform smoke and mirrors</ul></ul>

<ul><a href="#spoof">Tesla, Nikola</a><br>
<ul>Croatian-born Nikola Tesla instrumental in acceptance of
alternating current</ul></ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><b><i>Summary:</b></i>&nbsp;&nbsp;The summary is just that, a full-text summarizing of the texts most significant ideas
presented in sequence, with the original texts structure maintained.  Each paragraph of the
summary is hot-linked to the originating paragraph in the text.  Headings can, at the engineers
option, be included, and when included they are also hot-linked to the original text.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><b><i>Table of Contents:</i></b>&nbsp;&nbsp;The table of contents is a presentation of the headings in outline form to
render the texts overall structure and scope.  Headings are all hot-linked, and successive heading
levels are represented by successive indents:<p>

<a name="spoof2"></a>
<p><a href="#spoof2">
<ul>General Trade Agreements<br>
<ul>Preface<br>
Textiles<br>
<ul>Cotton products<br>
Man-made fabrics<br></ul>
General Manufactured Goods</a></ul></ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>


<center><h3>API Access</h3></center>

<p>SWAPI provides two level of API access: the stream level I/O option provides the programmer
with the greatest flexibility; the file level I/O option provides the programmer the simplest
access.  At the stream level, the programmer passes a buffer to SWAPI, which processes the
buffer and returns it to the calling program.  The calling program can collect the processed data
at this time or wait until all buffers have been processed.  All the linguistic analysis is done at
this level and all the hyperlinks are written, but the output is not formatted.  At the file level, the
programmer passes an HTML file list to SWAPI, which processes the files and returns them to
the calling program, passing back HTML files that are pre-formatted (according to the options
set by the programmer).  The calling program can do additional output formatting if required.</p>
<hr width="25%">
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<a name="options"><h2>SWAPI Options</h2>

<p>The following options are available at both the stream and the file level.</p>

<p><b><i>Types of output:</b></i>&nbsp;&nbsp;The engineer can select any or all of SWAPIs output typesindex, concept
index, summary, and table of contents.</p>

<p><b><i>Output level:</i></b>&nbsp;&nbsp;Each form of output can be separately adjusted for its degree of
comprehensiveness.</p>

<p><b><i>Circular links:</i></b>&nbsp;&nbsp;Circular links provide another means of handling duplicate entries in an index.
When a key term is indexed multiple times, circular links allow the end-user to jump from the
index (where the key term is listed only once) to the first instance of the term, from the first
instance to the second instance, and so on through each significant use of the term in the text,
until finally the last instance of the term is linked back to the index, completing the circle.
Circular links can be established for entries in the index or the concept index.</p>

<p><b><i>Horizontal links:</b></i>&nbsp;&nbsp;Horizontal links allow the end-user to jump from a key term in the index to the
place where that term appears in the summary, and from the summary on to the full text if
desired.</p>

<p><b><i>Personal names:</i></b>&nbsp;&nbsp;Personal names can be indexed, or suppressed from indexing.</p>

<P><b><i>Geographical names:</i></b>&nbsp;&nbsp;Recognized geographical names can be indexed, or suppressed from
indexing.</p>

<p><b><i>User-defined control list:</i></b>&nbsp;&nbsp;Syntacticas output can be refined by the use of  user-defined control
lists which allow the user to set the relative indexing importance of any words they choose.
Control lists are especially helpful when indexing documents from very technical fields.</p>

<p><b><i>Compound words:</i></b>&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition to its standard word-by-word analysis of the text, Syntactica can
be instructed to look for compound words (e.g., control tower, hot dog).  This is not a statistical
count of frequency and proximity, however; only compounds in the main lexicon or in a user-
defined control list will be recognized.</p>

<p><b><i>Unknown words:</i></b>&nbsp;&nbsp;SWAPI can be instructed to create a database consisting of the words found in
the text which are not in SWAPIs internal lexicon.  This database can then be opened in
LexEdit, a lexicon maintenance utility provided with SWAPI, and the words properly identified
for reprocessing.  (It should be noted here that Syntactica includes a fairly large section of code
for disambiguating and handling unknown words, so that the presence of unknown words will
not generally cause any major problems in the output.  Nonetheless, identifying and properly
classifying those unknown words will assure more accurate parsing of the text.)</p>
<hr width="25%">
<p>&nbsp;</p>

<a name="enhance"><h2>Projected Enhancements</h2></a>

<p>Over the last two years Iconovex has divided its development efforts between improving access
to and output from our APIs, on the one hand, and building applications which make use of those
APIs.  These applications have twice won Byte Magazines Best of Comdex award 
AnchorPage as Best Development Software (Spring, 1995), and EchoSearch as Best New
Internet Product (Spring, 1996).  These products are both based on SWAPI technology, yet make
distinctly different uses of it, thereby demonstrating its flexibility.</p>

<p>Further development and refinement of SWAPI technologyboth in its Natural Language
Processing and in the hypertext tools through which the language output is controlled and
presentedcontinues to be central to Iconovexs future business plans.  In the course of the next
year we plan to make significant improvements in the following areas:</p>
<ul>
<li><i>speed and footprint:</i>  Over the last six months we have reduced the size of the core
linguistic engine by over 50% while increasing its speed tenfold.  We are still
working on both optimizations, but especially on increasing speed.
<li><I>main lexicon:</i>  The lexicon at the heart of our language processing contains
approximately 130,000 entries.  We can reasonably hope to increase this by 10,000
to 40,000 entries over the next year, a great many of them compound words.  This
will help to increase the accuracy of our parsing as well as our evaluation of
significance for indexing and summarizing purposes.
<li><i>linguistic analysis:</i>  Increasing the sophistication of our linguistic analysis is an
ongoing process.  We currently have detailed specifications for the next six months
of development and broader, more general specifications for the year following that.
While our principal goal is simply to improve overall analysis, we will specifically
be targeting improvement of analysis over a wider range of document formats and
subject matters.
<li><i>hypertext editing:</i>  Over the next 6  9 months we will be adding hypertext editing
tools which will allow easier pre-process and post-process control over the final
output.  Pre-process tools will include an exclusion zone editor which will allow the
user to mark sections of text as exempt from indexing.  Post-processing tools will
include an entry editor which will make adding, deleting, or altering individual
entries easier and less time consuming.
<li><i>keyword search:</i>  We will shortly be adding a keyword search function to SWAPI
which will make our output searchable as well as browsable.  A query form will be
presented to the user, through which he or she can enter terms to be searched for.  A
stemmer will then be applied to those terms to derive their base terms and all of the
inflected forms.  All of these terms will then be matched against a hierarchical
lexical database in order to find related words, which will then be added to the
original query terms.  Finally, this expanded set of query terms will be run against a
keyword database built from all the significant terms in the index and concept index
and the user will be presented with a qualified index (or concept index) in which all
of the displayed entries are directly related to his or her query terms.
</ul>
<hr width="25%">
<p>&nbsp;</p>



<a name="products"><h2>Iconovex Products that Use SWAPI</h2></a>

<p>Three of Iconovexs current products are built on SWAPI and can serve as examples of the uses
to which the technology can be put.  Potential uses, of course, are limited only by the size and
scope of a developers imagination.</p>

<p><b><i>EchoSearch</i></b> uses SWAPIs linguistic analysis to turn its multi-threaded, multi-search
capabilities into intelligent searching.  Using Javas multi-threading, EchoSearch takes a users
query, submits it to multiple search engines at once, downloads the hit list from each of the
engines, and then proceeds to download the documents themselves.  But, what gives EchoSearch
its extra edge is the linguistic analysis it does after downloading the documents.  EchoSearch
analyzes and indexes the entire document suite, and then filters the resulting index with the
query terms.  But the result is not a simple list of index entries reading multiple sclerosis.  Any
good string-matching algorithm could do that.  Using SWAPIs more sophisticated analysis,
EchoSearch presents an index of all the significant terms which were found in concepts related to
multiple sclerosis.  These, then, are qualified index entries; the researcher can browse the index
knowing that all the terms listed are in some way related to the search query.</p>

<p>In a recent trial run, for instance, the query multiple sclerosis returned an index which
included, among other things, the index terms aluminum and mercury, both of which led
back to an article which included the phrase:</p>

<blockquote>. . . a prominent theory relates heavy metals like mercury, lead and
aluminum as the agents that might replace normal molecules in the myelin
sheaths, leading to an onslaught of free radical damage which destroys the
myelin sheaths, resulting in MS.</blockquote>


<p><b><i>AnchorPage</i></b> is a server-side product that makes all four of SWAPIs primary outputs available
to the user, typically the Webmaster of a site with a large volume of text that needs to be
organized and made accessible to users.  As HTML increasingly becomes the de facto standard
on corporate Intranets, AnchorPage will serve the same purpose in that environment.  At present,
AnchorPage is being used as the primary access vehicle for a catalog of scientific books,
corporate employee handbooks, and OSHA regulations.</p>

<p><b><i>WebAnchor</i></b> is primarily a client-side organizational tool for word processed or online
documents, though it is also being used on some corporate Intranets as a server product.
WebAnchor provides only the basic indexing output (with hyperlinking, of course).  On the
client side, it can be used by individual users on their PCs to index documents they have created
within a word processor, downloaded from the net (thus providing them with a way of efficiently
finding the facts they are after without having to read through a lot of unrelated information), or
to supply indexes for HTML documents they have created.  Since all the major online services
now provide some space for individual home pages, and most universities are beginning to do so,
we expect that this latter use of WebAnchor will become much more common.  The individual
who writes a lengthy report, a thesis, a dissertation, or a professional article and wishes to
publish it on the Web will be able to publish it with a hyperlinked index with virtually no extra
effort on his or her part.</p>
<hr width="25%">
<p>&nbsp;</p>



<a name="advantages"><h2>Advantages of the SWAPI Approach</h2></a>

<p>SWAPI offers a unique blend of technologies perfectly suited to the
Information Age.  It is ideal whether you are developing software for the
Internet or for corporate intranets, for a Webmaster trying to make
information available or an end-user trying to find that information.
SWAPI is a fast, reliable, and accurate way to turn today's continual
stream of electronic data into organized and accessible information.</p>

<p>For server-side products, SWAPI can make it possible to promptly
publish information that is <i>meaningfully</i> indexed and fully
hyperlinked.  Not only does this make that information more readily
accessible than through a search engine run against an inverted index, it
makes user access to that information considerably less demanding on server
resources.</p>

<p>For client-side products, SWAPI can provide the ability to sort through
undifferentiated masses of data, determine the significant concepts, and
gain instant access to those concepts through hypertext links. SWAPI finds
the facts, not just the words.</p>
<hr width="25%">
<p>&nbsp;</p>


<a name="corporate"><h2>Corporate History</h2></a>

<p>Iconovex, incorporated in 1994, is a software development company
specializing in Natural Language Processing software.  Our core technology,
the Syntactica engine, was in development for 18 years before Iconovex
acquired it.  Its original developers, Arnie Schultz and Don Malcolm, are
still employed by the company.  Iconovex now has 26 full-time employees
based in Bloomington, Minnesota.</p>

<p>In addition to the SWAPI-based products discussed earlier in this paper,
Iconovex also sells Indexicon, a word processor-based indexing product.
Now in its second release, Indexicon is available for Microsoft Word and
WordPerfect, and will soon be ported to Framemaker.</p>

<p>The Iconovex Corporation is a wholly-owned subsidiary of Innovex, Inc.,
the world's leading manufacturer of lead wire assemblies for the
high-growth thin film disk drive market. Founded in 1972, Innovex has over
500 employees. Its NASDAQ symbol is INVX. </p>
<hr width="25%">
