<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>AnchorPage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" link="#0000FF"
vlink="#663399">
<h1><img src="ANCR.GIF" align=LEFT>AnchorPage Product
Description & Specifications Sheet</H1><HR>
<a name="MENU">
<h2><center><b>Making Large Document Databases Accessible to the World
Wide Web</b></center></h2><ul>
<li><A HREF="#INTRO">Introduction to AnchorPage</a>
<li><a href="#AUTO">Fully Automatic, Completely Customizable</a>
<li><a href="#CDN">What is <i>Content-Driven Navigation</i>?</a>
<li><A HREF="#NAVVIEWS">What are <i>Navigational Views</I>?</A>
<li><A HREF="#ADMIN">Features and Benefits <I>For the Web Site
Administrator</I></A>
<li><A HREF="#ENDUSER">Features and Benefits <I>For the Web Site
End-User</I></A>
<LI><A HREF="#TECHSPEC">System Requirements</A>
<LI><A HREF="#CONTACT">Contact Information</a></ul>
<PRE>


</PRE>
<BR><A NAME="INTRO"><H2>Introduction</h2><H3>Automate and Improve your Web
Publishing!</H3>AnchorPage is the ONLY automatic indexing, abstracting and
hyperlinking software for the Web. It saves site maintenance time by
automatically indexing, abstracting and hyperlinking the key concepts
and phrases in your HTML documents.<br>AnchorPage will also improve your
site by
introducing truly "webbed" information and <a href="#CDN">Content-Driven
Navigation</a> to your visitors. Because your AnchorPaged documents
have been inter/intra-linked, visitors to your site are not only linked
"to" your documents; they can follow links "within" and
"between" the documents. <p>
AnchorPage extracts the significant phrases and concepts from
each of your World Wide Web documents, <u><em>automatically</em></u>
inserts hypertext anchors for each of those phrases and concepts,
and produces four <a href="#NAVVIEWS"><i>Navigational Views</i></A> of the
document; a
Table of Contents view, Phrase view, Concept view, and Abstract view.
Each entry in these Navigational Views is hyperlinked to its
occurrence in the original document.
<p><a href="#MENU"><IMG SRC="UP.GIF" ALT=ARROW> Return to Menu</a>
<pre>



</pre>
<A NAME="AUTO">
<h2><b>Fully Automatic, Completely Customizable</b></h2>
<p>

<p>
The AnchorPage process can be divided into three distinct phases:  1)
parsing the document, 2) placing hypertext anchors in the document,
and 3) building navigational pages that link to these anchors.  Each
of these phases is fully automatic, yet each allows you to tailor
the output to suit your own needs and preferences.
<p>
You control AnchorPage's determination of what constitutes a significant
concept or phrase through a simple Selection Threshold setting.
You can also direct AnchorPage to give more or less weight to
specific terms and phrases by building a control list with LexEdit,
a lexicon utility provided with AnchorPage.
<p>
You control which Navigational Views are created and the nature of
the hypertext links between them.  You can also create circular
links within the presentation document so that your user can jump
through the document following a single concept as it develops.
<p>
We provide alternate templates so that you can easily change the
appearance of the final pages that will appear on your server.
Each of these templates can be customized, or you can substitute
pages of your own design.
<p><a href="#MENU"><IMG SRC="UP.GIF" ALT=ARROW> Return to Menu</a>
<PRE>


</PRE>
<p><A NAME="NAVVIEWS">
<h2>What are <i>Navigational Views</i>?</h2>
<p>

Navigational Views represent different entry points into a document.
The <a href="#toc">Table of Contents View</a> presents the document
headings and
subheadings in outline form.  The <a href="#abs">Abstract View</a> presents
abstracts of the
significant concepts in the order in which they appear in the original
document.
<a href="#conc">The Concept View</a> presents the significant concepts in
context and alphabetized according
to the keywords they contain.  <a href="#phr">The Phrase View</a> is an
alphabetical
listing of the keywords and key phrases drawn from the concepts.
These Navigational Views can then be linked to each other and to
the Presentation page, a view of the document in its presentation
form.
<p>
The mini-paragraphs below illustrate the different Navigational
Views with a small sampling of actual AnchorPage entries for an article on
the Cold War taken from Microsoft <i>Encarta</i> Encyclopedia.
<p><a name="toc">
<h3>Table of Contents View: The Cold War</h3>
<menu>
<strong>Background</strong>
<br>
<strong>Moves and Countermoves</strong>
<br>
<strong>Thaws and Freezes</strong>
</menu>
<pre>


</pre><a name="phr">
<h3>Phrase View:  The Cold War</h3>
<menu>
<strong>Communism</strong>
<br>
<strong>East-West conflict</strong>
<br>
<strong>Domestic pressures</strong>
<br>
<strong>Nuclear forces</strong>
<br>
<strong>Vietnam War</strong>:  U.S. involvement in
</menu>
<pre>


</pre><a name="conc">
<h3>Concept View: The Cold War</h3>
<menu>
<strong>Communism</strong>: War undertaken as part of effort to stem perceived
worldwide threat of communism
<p>
<strong>Domestic pressures</strong>:  Rising costs of arms race and other
domestic pressures helped bring U.S. and Soviet leaders to the
negotiating table
<p>
<strong>East-West Conflict</strong>:  East-West conflict assumed form
of more traditional struggle
<p>
<strong>Treaty</strong>:  Meetings between superpowers led in December 1987
to signing of treaty to eliminate intermediate-range nuclear forces
<p>
<strong>Vietnam</strong>:  Mistrust shaped U.S. involvement in Vietnam
War
</menu>
<pre>


</pre>
<a name="abs">
<h3>Abstract View:  The Cold War</h3>
<menu>
<strong>Mistrust shaped U.S. involvement in Vietnam War</strong> . . .
<P>
<strong>Undertaken as part of effort to stem perceived worldwide threat
of communism</strong>
<P>
<strong>East-West conflict assumed form of more traditional struggle</strong> . . .
<P>
<strong>Rising costs of arms race and other domestic pressures helped
bring U.S. and Soviet leaders to negotiating table</strong> . . .
<P>
<strong>Meetings between superpowers led in December 1987 to
signing of treaty to eliminate intermediate-range nuclear forces</strong> . . .
</menu><P><a href="#MENU"><IMG SRC="UP.GIF" ALT=ARROW> Return to Menu</a>
<pre>


</pre>

<p><a name="CDN"><center><h2>What is <i>Content-Driven
Navigation</i>?</h2></CENTER>
<b><i>Content-Driven Navigation</i></b> is a new and exciting way to browse
web sites. Browsing a web site usually involves either
investigating different directories by traversing from
document to document or it involves using a search engine to look for
something in particular. Both methods are effective and will, more
often than not, bring you to an interesting document or keyword. However;
once you've been brought <b>to</b> the document, you are left to download or
scroll through it on your own. AnchorPage introduces<b> <i>Content-Driven
Navigation</i></b> to let you travel <b>within</b> and <b>throughout</b> a
document (or suite of
documents). You are now able to trace a concept, phrase or abstract,
weaving in and out of truly "webbed" information. You can enter the
<a href="#abs">Abstract View</a> of a document and quickly evaluate
whether or not you'd like to delve deeper; enter the <a
href="#conc">Concept View</a> and determine whether the
keyword you're looking for exists in the context you're looking for it
in. Examine the back-of-the-book index <a href="#phr">Phrase View</a>
to be immediately hyperlinked to a specific term. The <a
href="#toc">Table of Contents View</a> offers you immediate
access to all of the headings of the document; a familiar and welcome
way of viewing the main sections of information. All
four of the <a href="#NAVVIEWS">Navigational Views</a> that comprise
<b><I>Content-Driven Navigation</b></i> represent separate entry points
to your documents' content yet they are intertwined through hypertext to
offer complete exploration <b>within</b> and <b>throughout</b> the
documents' content. <p><a href="#MENU"><IMG SRC="UP.GIF" ALT=ARROW>
Return to Menu</a> <pre>






</pre>
<p><a name="ADMIN"> <center><h2>Features
and Benefits</h2> <p> <h3>For the Web Site Administrator</h3></center>
<p>

<ul>
<li><b>AnchorPage is fast.</b>   For example, it analyzed a 600K document
on a 66MHz PC in just 9-1/2 minutes! This makes it possible to process
entire document databases overnight.  New documents can be added in a
matter of minutes, which means that a server using AnchorPage can always
have the most current and up-to-date information on-line in value-added
form with no extra administrative overhead.
<li><b>The process is fully automatic.</b>   Once the administrator
has set his or her preferred options, the entire process  from
analyzing the documents to placing hypertext links to producing
the navigational pages the end user will see is fully automatic.
<li><b>The administrator controls the look as well as the
content of the final product.</b>   The site administrator can
choose any or all of the four Navigational Views to present.  The
amount of detail in those Views can be set at six different
levels.  The format of the Synopsis pages can also be
customized to reflect the administrators preferences.
<li><b>Documents can be processed individually or in suites.</b>
Documents can be processed individually, producing Navigational Views
for each document, or in suites, producing integrated Navigational
Views for the entire suite.
<li><b>Entries can be tailored to emphasize different
interests and priorities.</b>    LexEdit, a utility provided with
AnchorPage, allows the administrator to alter the analysis performed
on documents through the use of control lists of terms he or she
may consider of special importance.
<li><b>Files can be located anywhere on your system.</b>
Easy-to-use file selection windows allow the administrator to
choose files anywhere on the server to assemble a suite of documents
for processing.
<li><b>Documents are segmented for faster download times.</b>
All of AnchorPage's output pages; the four Navigational Views and
the Presentation View of the original document, can be segmented
to allow faster download times for your users and fuller control
over the complete document for you.  Segmentation is completely
adjustable, allowing you to specify whatever size segment you think
most suitable for your documents and your users' needs.
<li><b>No modification to your existing pages is necessary.</b>
AnchorPage forms a seamless link between your document menu page
and the actual documents, but doesn't otherwise affect the structure
or organization of your server.  You need not rewrite your homepage, or
any other pages, to get the full benefit.
<li><b>Satisfied users make for a popular Web site.</b>
News travels fast on the Web, especially news of a good site with
readily accessible information.  When you make it possible for
users to find what they want quickly, easily, and reliably, you
assure not only that they will revisit your site, but also that
they will tell others about it.
<li><b>Browser included.</b>   A Windows-compatible browser
is included for easy viewing and testing of navigational pages and
their hypertext links.
<li><b>Converts RTF files.</b>  AnchorPage also includes <B>RTFact</b>,
an easy-to-use program which converts RTF files to HTML format.
</ul>
<p><a href="#MENU"><IMG SRC="UP.GIF" ALT=ARROW> Return to Menu</a><PRE>



</PRE>
<P><A NAME="ENDUSER">
<center><h2>Features and Benefits</h2>
<p>
<h3>For the Web Site End-User</h3></center>
<p>

<ul>
<li><b>Users find the right document every time.</b>
With AnchorPage Navigational Views, users can scan a table of contents,
significant words and phrases, significant concepts, even abstracts
before deciding which documents they want to view or download.
Users will no longer be forced to rely on a list of nondescript
titles as the basis for selecting documents.
<li><b>Users save reading time and downloading time.</b>
Navigational pages can be retrieved in a fraction of the time it would
take to retrieve the full document, and users can skim or search
on those pages quickly and easily, getting straight to
the essence of any document's contents.  No more time (or money)
wasted downloading documents that prove unusable.
<li><b>Timely documents are available in a timely fashion.</b>
Because AnchorPage is fast and automatic, administrators will
be able to place online the most timely documents fully indexed and
hyperlinked within hours of their availability.  Users
will appreciate, and come to rely upon, this speedy access to
up-to-date information.
</ul>
<p><a href="#MENU"><IMG SRC="UP.GIF" ALT=ARROW> Return to Menu</a><PRE>



</PRE>
<A NAME="TECHSPEC">

<h2>System Requirements</h2>
<p>
<ul>
<li>486 Processor or better
<li>Microsoft  Windows 3.1x, WFW 3.1x, Windows 95, or Windows NT
<li>8MB RAM (Windows 3.1x, WFW 3.1x, & Windows 95)--16 MB RAM (Windows NT)
<li>Documents in RTF or HTML format
<li>Win32s 1.30x (Windows 3.1 users only).  For more information see our
<a href="../TECHSUPP.HTM#Win32s">Technical Support area</a>
</ul>

<a href="#MENU"><IMG SRC="UP.GIF" ALT=ARROW> Return to
Menu</a><PRE>




</PRE>

