<html>
<head>
<title>Court's Decision on the Communications Decency Act</title>
<body>
<h2>Court's Decision on the Communications Decency Act</h2>
<hr>
<p>
Recently (June 12, 1996), a three-judge panel in Philadelphia handed down
a ruling on the case of the American Civil Liberties Union vs. Janet Reno,
where the ACLU, among many others, had challenged the constitutionality
of the controversial "Communications Decency Act" that was part of the
Telecommunications Reform Bill.  The judges ruled that the "CDA" was
<b>unconstitutional</b> and ordered it struck down.  Presented here is their
written ruling; regardless of which side you take in this issue, it's
interesting reading.  The issue is by no means closed; the goverment is
expected to appeal the decision to the Supreme Court.
<p>
<h3><a href="CDA/CDADEC.HTM">The Court's Decision Regarding the
Communications Decency Act</a>.</H3>  The full text of the decision, 
one document.  Note: this is a <em>big</em> file (256K). <p>
<h3><a href="CDA/HOME.HTM">The Court's Decision Regarding the
Communications Decency Act</a>.</h3>
The same document, run through AnchorPage with the following settings:
<ul>
<li>Phrase, Concept, Abstract, and Table of Contents Views were all enabled.
<li>All Selectivity levels were set at 3, except for Phrase, which was set at 2.
<li>Both Phrase and Concept "A - Z" pages were used.
<li>"Phrase Circular Links" and "Phrase Horizontal Links" were selected.
<li>The "Default" icon template was used.
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
