<html>
<head>
<title>Frequently Asked Questions</title>
 </head> <body bgcolor="FFCC99" link="6600CC"
vlink="996600">
<center><H3>
EchoSearch FAQ</H3></center>
<hr>
<UL>
<UL type=circ>
<LI>
<A HREF="#UPGRADE" >Upgrade Questions</A></LI>
<LI>
<A HREF="#PROGRAM" >General Program Questions</A></LI>
<LI>
<A HREF="#OUTPUT" >General Output Questions</A></LI>
<LI>
<A HREF="#BROWSER" >Browser-related Questions</A></LI>
<LI>
<A HREF="#IAP" >Internet Access Provider Questions</A></LI>
<LI>
<A HREF="#QUALIFIED" >Qualified Results Questions</A></LI>
<LI>
<A HREF="#INDEX" >Index View Questions</A></LI>
<LI>
<A HREF="#TOC" >Table of Contents Questions</A></LI>
<LI>
<A HREF="#FACSIMILE" >Facsimile Questions</A></LI>
</UL>

<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="UPGRADE"></A>

<h3><b>Upgrade Questions</b></h3>
<p><b>Q: How to I upgrade to a more recent version of EchoSearch?</b>
<p><B>A:</b> If you have not yet registered your copy of EchoSearch, you
must do so to become eligible for online upgrades.  If you do have a
<b>registered</b> copy of EchoSearch and you have version <b>1.04 or
higher</b>, you must upgrade from within EchoSearch. For step-by-step
instructions, go to <A HREF="ESORDER.HTM#ONUPGRADE">How to Upgrade Your Copy
of EchoSearch</a>. If you own a registered copy of EchoSearch 1.03 or
older and wish to upgrade, click <a href="ESORDER.HTM#OLD">here</a>.<p> <br>
<br> <A NAME="PROGRAM"></A>

<H3><B>General EchoSearch Questions</B></H3>

<A ID="E11E15" NAME="E11E15"></A>
<P><B>Q: I am running Windows 95 and am getting Invalid Page Faults (or
General Protection Faults) when running EchoSearch for a long time, or when
I run a large search and download many documents.  Is there anything I can
do?</B> <P><B>A:</B> Microsoft has an update for Windows 95 that resolves a
memory leak which occurs when opening and closing a Socket using the Windows
Sockets API.  This update is called the Kernel32 Update.
<P>Visit the <a
href="http://www.microsoft.com/windows/software/krnlupd.htm">Windows 95
Updates page</a> for more information and to download this Kernel32 Update.
<B>Note: </B>You will need to have your Internet connection open in order to
view this page or to download this file. <p>
</td></tr></table> <B>Q: Is there any way I can
speed up the analysis step?</B> <P><B>A:</B> EchoSearch will be able to
process documents retrieved from a search more quickly if you close any other
applications before EchoSearch begins download and analysis.

<A ID="E11E23" NAME="E11E23"></A>
<P><B>Q: I am getting frequent &quot;Error&quot; Status Messages from a search
engines.  Why?</B><A ID="E16E74" NAME="E16E74"></A>
<P><B>A: </B>If you
are receiving repeated &quot;Error&quot; messages from a search engine, or if
the search engine repeatedly responds with &quot;Done&quot; almost
immediately for different queries, you should see if an updated driver is
available for that engine. You can retrieve search engine updates and
additions from the Iconovex Web site at any time by choosing <B>Update
</B><B>Now </B>(on the Search Engines dialog).

<P><b>A: </b>If you are getting an &quot;Error&quot; message from a search
engine <i>clone</i> that you created, you may have indicated the wrong search
query URL.  Verify that the URL in the <b>Enter URL to which query is
submitted</b> box is correct.<p>
<b>Q: Can EchoSearch use my Intranet version of a search engine?</b>
<p><b>A: </b>Currently EchoSearch only supports AltaVista's Intranet search
engine.  Refer to <a href="CLONES.HTM">Search Engines Clone page</a> for
information on clones supported by EchoSearch.  Instructions on how to add
search engine clones is also available in the online help.  If you would like
to see a clone of a search engine supported by EchoSearch added to
EchoSearch's search engine list, send us your request using the <a
href="SENGINE.HTM">Search Engine Request form</a>.

<A ID="E11E24" NAME="E11E24"></A>
<P><B>Q: Why did I get a "Network Error" during downloading?</B><A ID="E16E76"
NAME="E16E76"></A>
<P><B>A: </B>When EchoSearch is unable to download a document, it
will be displayed as a network error in the Progress: Download and Analysis
dialog.  You can view the document URLs that returned network errors in the
statistics file.  To open the statistics file, open your search results and
click on the <B>Statistics </B>link at the top of the page.

<A NAME="E15E171"></A>
<P><B>Q: I repeat a search that I've run earlier and I get different results. Why?</B>
<A NAME="E15E172"></A>
<P><B>A:</B> Identical queries submitted to the same set of search engines will
sometimes return a different set of document hits, depending on the breadth of your
query and the number of hits you requested. Generally speaking, if you request a
large number of documents for a narrow topic (50 documents on &quot;Grand Marais&quot;)
you will get fairly consistent results with each repeated query because there are
fewer than 50 documents available on Grand Marais, and you will get the same set of
documents returned each time. If you request a small number of documents for a broad
subject (10 documents on &quot;basketball&quot;), you are likely to get rather
different results with searches because each search engine may list hundreds of
documents on basketball, and the document set you get will depend entirely on which
search engine responds most quickly to the query.

<p>
<b>Q:  On my machine, Netscape runs just fine, but EchoSearch claims it
can't connect to any of the search engines whenever I try to do a search.</b>
<p>
<b>A:</b>  If you're using EchoSearch at work, it's possible that your
machine at work is using a <i>Proxy Server</i>.  EchoSearch can
compensate for this, however; contact your systems administrator and find
out if you're using a proxy server, and if so what its <b>IP
address</b> and <b>port number</b> are.  Once you have this
information, click on the "Options" menu, and select the
item "Network Settings."  In this dialog box, check the "user
proxy server" box.  Enter the IP address and port number of the proxy
server in the appropriate blanks and click <b>OK</b>.  That should
take care of the problem.

<BR><BR>
<A NAME="OUTPUT"></A>

<H3><B>General Output Questions</B></H3>


<A NAME="E15E175"></A>
<P><B>Q: Sometimes the links on the Qualified Results (or Index page or
Concept page) take me to the right part of the document, </B><B>but the
actual words I clicked on aren't at the top of the browser page. Why aren't
the words I'm looking for always right at </B><B>the top of the browser page?</B>

<A NAME="E15E176"></A>
<P><B>A:</B> Most often this occurs because the words you're looking for are
near the end of the document. As long as the document fills at least one
screen, the browser will not display any empty space after the end of the
document (that is, the last line in the document must always be at the
bottom of the last screenful in the browser). If the term you are looking
for is anywhere in the last screenful of the document, the browser will not
allow the line containing that term to be brought to the top of the display,
but will simply show the last full screen of the document.

<A
NAME="E15E177"></A> <P><B>Q: Why are there duplicate entries in my EchoSearch
output?</B> <A NAME="E15E178"></A> <P><B>A:</B> EchoSearch detects duplicate
documents by matching the URLs, and it eliminates these duplicates from the
search engines' hit list. However, some documents may be found in more than
one place on the Web, in which case each separate location will have a
separate URL. EchoSearch has no way of detecting this. The result will be
duplicate entries, one entry for each copy of the document.

<A NAME="E15E179"></A> <P><B>Q: Why do I get entries in
the Concept View and Qualified Results where words are repeated over and
over?</B>

<A NAME="E15E180"></A> <P><B>A:</B> In an effort to increase the
likelihood that a document will be considered a &quot;hit&quot; by search
engines, some Webmasters may include text that has nothing but keywords
repeated over and over again. When an author has used this method of
attracting search engines, coined &quot;spamdexing,&quot; you will often find
strange entries in your search results, where a word or phrase is repeated
over and over. If you then click on one of these entries, you may jump to a
paragraph that is unrelated to the entry or to a paragraph that appears
&quot;empty&quot;, because the original text was hidden by the author so that
it would not be visible in a browser (to locate the entry in the original
document, use the &quot;View Source&quot; or similar option to view the HTML
source and then use the &quot;Find&quot; feature, often <b>CTRL + F</b>). <A
NAME="E15E181"></A> <P>While we do our best to filter out this kind of
material, we cannot filter it out completely without the risk of eliminating
truly valid index entries contained in spamedexed documents. <A
NAME="E15E182"></A> <P>Some authors also use spamdexing in their document
titles. This will not cause problems in the index or concept outputs, but may
return some strange entries in the Summary view because EchoSearch simply
takes the title of the document (however long or ridiculous it might be) and
sticks it at the top of the summary. <A NAME="E11E7"></A> <A
NAME="BROWSER"></A> <BR><BR> <H3>Browser-related Questions</H3>

<P><B>Q: Why do some of my EchoSearch links not work even though I have
loaded Netscape 2.0 over my Netscape 1.2?</B></p>

<P><B>A:</B> Netscape Navigator 2.0 creates a new directory when it is
loaded called C:\Netscape\Programs.  The browser resides in this directory.
Netscape 2.0 will not overwrite a previous version of Netscape that resides
in the C:\Netscape directory.  You must specify the Netscape 2.0 browser that
resides in the C:\Netscape\Programs directory for your EchoSearch links to
work properly.

<P><B>Q: Why do I get the message &quot;Netscape is unable to locate
the server&quot; when I click on "View Original Document"?</B>
<p><B>A: </B>You may have been disconnected from your Internet connection.
If you are trying to view a document facsimile, your browser is most likely
attempting to display the ad for the sponsor of the search engine that
located the document.  In this case it is not necessary to reestablish your
connection; just "Stop" loading the page in your browser or click
<B>Cancel</B> when prompted to reconnect.

<P><B>A: (Windows 95)</B> If you are using
Windows 95 Dial-Up Networking, check your network settings. Go to the Control
Panel and double-click on &quot;Network.&quot; Highlight &quot;Dial-up
Adapter&quot; and click &quot;Properties.&quot;  On the Bindings tab, you
should only have ONE entry, &quot;TCP/IP.&quot;

<p><b>A: (Windows 95)</b> You also might not have a
16550 compatible UART (the chip that controls the modem connection). If you
do not, choose Start-Settings-Control Panel. Double-click on the Modems icon.
Select your modem and click &quot;Properties.&quot; Select the Connection tab
and then select &quot;Port Settings.&quot;  Uncheck the &quot;Use FIFO
buffers&quot; box.  Click <B>OK</B> three times to exit.

<p><b>Q: Why didn't my browser automatically come up when EchoSearch was
done processing?</b>
<p><b>A: </b>When Windows NT users are running EchoSearch with Netscape 2.0
minimized or in the background, the Netscape 2.0 window will not automatically
become the active window after EchoSearch has finished processing; users must
manually select the Netscape window.  Windows 95 users will not experience
this problem.  This problem will not occur for Windows NT if they are using
Netscape Navigator 2.01.</p>

<p>
<b>Q: EchoSearch runs just fine, but when it finishes, and I click on the
button to launch my browser to view the results, I get a long error
message that tells me that my browser can't find the file
"c:\Iconovex\EchoSearch\{whatever other pathname is involved}."  What's
wrong?</b>
<p>
<b>A:</b> The most likely answer is that you are using a 16-bit browser,
whereas EchoSearch requires a 32-bit browser (32-bit browsers are, on the
whole, the only browsers that can recognize long filenames, and
EchoSearch uses long filenames routinely); just because you're running
Windows 95, don't assume that all the software you're using is 32-bit.
Try downloading and installing the 32-bit version of your favorite browser
(don't worry; most such downloads are free).


<BR><BR>
<A NAME="IAP"></A>

<H3><B>Internet Access Provider Questions</B></H3>

<P><B>Q: How do I use EchoSearch with my Internet Access Provider?</B>
<p><B>A:</B> Refer to the Connect.html file that was installed with
EchoSearch or read <a href="Connect.html">&quot;Instructions for Using EchoSearch with Online
Service Providers.&quot;</a><p>
<B>Q: If I am using an Online Service Provider, do I need to stay
connected the whole time EchoSearch is running?</B><p>
<B>A:</B> No.  You may disconnect <EM>after </EM>EchoSearch has downloaded
all of the requested documents.  All of the analysis is done offline.  You may
also view the results offline, including the facsimile of the original document
EchoSearch has created on your hard drive.  However, if the facsimile contains
external links (links to URLs out on the Web) and you wish to follow those links,
or you wish to view the original document, you will need to reestablish your
connection.
<P>
<B>Q: Why did EchoSearch connect to the wrong service provider?</B><p>
<B>A: (Windows 95)</B> If you have multiple service providers set up on your
system (e.g., CompuServe and Microsoft Network), you may have another
provider set up to establish your Internet connection.  Right-click on the
Internet icon on your desktop and select &quot;Properties&quot; (or open it
in Control Panel).  On the Options tab, check &quot;Autodial&quot; and select
the provider you want to use for your Internet connection.

<P> <B>Q: Why
doesn't EchoSearch disconnect from my Online Service Provider when I close
EchoSearch and/or my browser?</B><p> <B>A: </B>Some network connections, like
Windows 95 dial-up networking, require you to manually disconnect from the
network.

<BR><BR>
<A NAME="QUALIFIED"></A>


<H3><B>Qualified Results
Questions</B></H3> <A NAME="E15E191"></A> <P>

<B>Q: My Qualified Results page
has all sorts of entries that do not seem to be directly related to my query.
Why is this?</B> <A NAME="E15E192"></A>
<P><B>A:</B> There are several
possible reasons for this. If you include small, non-essential words in your
query (of, the, and) and they are not part of a larger phrase set off by
quotes, this can cause your Qualifed Results to contain all sorts of
irrelevant matter. For instance, the query<p> battle of +&quot;Wounded
Knee&quot;<p> will draw all sorts of irrelevant matter into the Qualified
Results that would not be drawn in if the query were <p>battle +&quot;Wounded
Knee&quot;<p> or <p>&quot;battle of Wounded Knee&quot;. <A
NAME="E15E193"></A> <P>It is also possible that synonyms from your query
terms are causing unrelated items in your Qualified Results. If the query you
used was <p>battle +&quot;Wounded Knee&quot;<p> the Qualified Results might
contain an entry for the &quot;fight against poverty&quot; because
&quot;fight&quot; is a synonym of battle. This would not happen if the query
was submitted as <p>&quot;battle of Wounded Knee&quot;<p> because there is no
synonym for the entire expression. <A NAME="E15E194"></A>

<P><B>Q: Nothing appears on the Qualified Results page. Why? </B>
<A NAME="E15E14"></A>
<P><B>A:</B> This may happen when you enter a compound search term and choose the
Index View for your Qualified Results. Some compounds are listed in reverse order
in the index. For example, if you entered &quot;Abraham Lincoln&quot; for your
query, the index might list it as &quot;Lincoln, Abraham,&quot; causing it not to
appear in the index the way you actually entered it. You can alleviate this problem
by entering the terms as separate queries or use the Concept View (recommended)
for your Qualified results. If you enter the terms as separate queries, you might
want to boost the number of documents that you retrieve.
<A NAME="E15E15"></A>
<P><B>A: </B>Another possibility is that in your search query you used punctuation
within quotation marks, for example:
<A NAME="E15E16"></A>
<P>&quot;Boulder, Colorado&quot;
<A NAME="E15E17"></A>
<P>&quot;John F. Kennedy&quot;
<A NAME="E15E18"></A>
<P>It is preferable to avoid using punctuation within quotation marks, e.g.,
enter the query as:
<A NAME="E15E19"></A>
<P>+Boulder +Colorado
<A NAME="E15E20"></A>
<P>+John +Kennedy
<A NAME="E15E21"></A>


<BR><BR>
<A NAME="INDEX"></A>

<H3><B>Index
View Questions</B></H3>

<A NAME="E15E187"></A> <P><B>Q: My index has lots of
misspellings and run-together words like &quot;andthe&quot; or
&quot;forthe.&quot; Why did EchoSearch index &quot;andthe&quot;
</B><B>anyway?  </B>
<A NAME="E15E188"></A> <P><B>A:</B> If there are lots of misspellings and
run-together words in the output, it probably means that you ran across one
of those all-too-common documents on the Web that someone threw up in a hurry
without spellchecking. If there are mistakes in the original, there will be
mistakes in all our output; we do not presume to rewrite the original in any
way. Why would we index words like &quot;andthe&quot;? Because we accept the
original document in good faith, we assume the author has intended this word,
and since we don't recognize it, we assume it is probably a technical term
beyond the scope of our lexicon. We also assume that a technical term beyond
the scope of our lexicon is something that should be indexed.
<BR><BR>
<A NAME="TOC"></A>

<H3><B>Table of Contents Questions</B></H3>

<P><B>Q: My Table of Contents view didn't show any headings for a document even though the document itself contains headings. </B><B>Why?</B>
<A NAME="E15E197"></A>
<P><B>A:</B> The Table of Contents view only displays headings that are properly marked with HTML heading tags. Authors will sometimes use other stylistic devices (larger fonts or bold or italics) to give text the appearance of headings, but EchoSearch wi






ll not consider these headings and will not display them in the Table of Contents view.
<A NAME="E15E198"></A>
<P>

<A NAME="FACSIMILE"></A>

<H3><B>Facsimile Questions</B></H3>

<P><B>Q: Some of the text on my facsimile page has disappeared or some of the links lead me to blank documents. Other output </B><B>looks just plain screwy. Why is this happening?</B>
<A NAME="E15E184"></A>
<P><B>A:</B> This problem may have to do with an outdated driver for one of
the search engines. Many search engines make changes to their service,
causing erratic and unusual results in EchoSearch. This problem may be
resolved by updating your search engine drivers. In order to update your
search engines, do the following:

<OL> <LI>Establish your connection to the
World Wide Web. </LI> <LI>Open EchoSearch. </LI> <LI>From the <B>Options
</B>menu select <B>Search Engines</B>.<B> </B></LI> <LI>On the Search Engines
dialog click on the <B>Update Now </B>button. </LI> <LI>The download should
be very brief, and at the end of the process you will be asked to click on
<B>OK </B>to save the updates. Click <B>OK </B>and you're done.</LI> </OL> <A
NAME="E15E185"></A> <P><B>Q: Clicking on the &quot;View Original
Document&quot; link on one of the output pages does not work. Why?</B> <A
NAME="E15E186"></A> <P><B>A:</B> You are most likely using an Online Service
Provider and have either been disconnected from the network, or you chose to
disconnect earlier. You must reestablish your Internet connection in order to
view the original document on the Web.

<P><b>Q: My facsimile pages all have broken links on them where the images
should be</b>
<P><b>A: </b>In order to save time, EchoSearch creates text-only facsimiles
of the original documents.  The broken links are only markers to let you
know that the original document has some image there.   If you wish to see
the images, simply go to the top of the fasimile page and click on the
"View original document" link.  The original document with all its images
intact will be displayed in your browser.


<br><br>
