<head>
<title>Distinctions between WebAnchor and AnchorPage</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3>Distinctions between WebAnchor and AnchorPage</h3>
<hr>
<p>

<b>WebAnchor</b> is designed to help explorers of the Web organize
and create a hypertext, back-of-the-book-style index of all the documents
that they might download and collect on their own machines.
If you are researching a particular topic and have downloaded a number
of web pages that you <u>think</u> might be useful to you, but you haven't
had time to examine them all closely, you can use <b>WebAnchor</b> to
build an index of the pages to get a quick, clear look at the overall
contents.  Since the index is standard HTML output, it may also
be used to create the same type of index for a Web site.
You are limited only to this one type of output, however.  In contrast,
<b>AnchorPage</b> not only creates a simple back-of-the-book-style index, but
also offers a Concept View, a Table of Contents View, and an Abstract/
Summary view.  This is designed to help Webmasters organize a very
large, content-heavy site.
<p>
<b>WebAnchor</b> is a tool that will create your own personal
Web of information for your desktop; it can even convert
your word-processed documents (once you save them as RTF format)
into HTML and automatically index and hyperlink them together.
<p>
<b>AnchorPage</b> is designed to assist in the organization of an entire
web site, or a web site's collection of documents; <b>WebAnchor</b>, while it can
be used in a similar fashion (with less detailed results) is more for the
use of the Web traveller who needs to organize what he or she finds.
<p>
<hr>
<a href="../WEBANCH.HTM">Return to WebAnchor page</a>
</body>
