<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>The Iconovex Corporation</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#ffffff"><P>&nbsp;
<P><CENTER></CENTER>

<H1>HTML Information and Utilities

</H1><P><HR> 

<H2>Converters, discussions, and sundries relating to the Hypertext Markup
Language

</H2><P>

<P>This page is by no means static; it is always open to change and improvement.
Please feel free (even obligated) to send me information on materials that
should appear on a page like this but don't.

<P><HR length=300>
<center>
<TABLE border=1	>
<tr><td align=center colspan=2><h3><a href="#1">General 
Sites</a></h3></td></tr> <tr>
<td ALIGN=CENTER><h3><a href="#3">HTML Tools</a></h3></td>
<td ALIGN=CENTER><h3><a href="#2">HTML Documentation</a></h3></td>
</tr>
<tr><td ALIGN=CENTER><h3><a href="#4">Discussion Groups and <br>
Style Guides</a></h3></td>
<td ALIGN=CENTER>
<h3><a href="#5">HTML Validators</a><img src="NEW_TINY.GIF" alt="New!">
</h3>
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<P><HR>

<PRE><P>




</PRE><H2><A name="1">General HTML Sites</A>
</H2><P><EM>Sites with information, software, and more. Some have multiple
links to other useful sites.</EM>

<P><A href="http://WWW.Stars.com/">The Web Developer's Virtual Library</A>

<BLOCKQUOTE>An excellent, comprehensive collection of links, tools, applications,
useful sites and collections of graphics for Web page development.  Get
ready to spend some time exploring here; there's a lot to cover, but it's
well laid-out.

</BLOCKQUOTE><P>
<A href="http://netvet.wustl.edu/hotlist.htm">Ken Boschert's Hotlist</A>

<BLOCKQUOTE>This is a <B>colossal</B> collection of Internet, Web, and HTML
related sites, put together by Ken Boschert, DVM, at Washington
University.  It's a bit overwhelming at times, but there are many extremely
useful links.

</BLOCKQUOTE><P>

<A HREF="http://www.ski.mskcc.org:80/browserwatch/">BrowserWatch</a>
<BLOCKQUOTE>A good place to keep up on the latest version of a large 
number of popular Web browsers.  This site keeps up-to-date records of 
the latest versions and, in some cases, brief reviews and rumors about 
different browsers.

</BLOCKQUOTE><P>


<A name="2"></A>
<H2>HTML Documentation

</H2><P><EM>Specifications, descriptions, backgrounds.</EM>

<P><A HREF=http://www.iconovex.com/HTML.HTM>What is
HTML?</A><!-- Remember to change this to d| -->

<BLOCKQUOTE>A very brief description and simple abstract of HTML.

</BLOCKQUOTE><P>

<P><A href="http://www.w3.org/hypertext/WWW/MarkUp/MarkUp.html">
Overview of HTML</A>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A large, rather technical overview from the Internet Engineering
Task Force (IETF). It describes the original purpose of HTML and gives some
of the original designs and schematics of HTML version 1.

</BLOCKQUOTE><P><A href="http://www.ics.uci.edu/pub/ietf/html/rfc1866.txt">HTML 2.0</A><BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A large (about 120k) text file that gives all the technical
schematics for HTML version 2.

</BLOCKQUOTE><P><A href="http://www.hpl.hp.co.uk/people/dsr/html3/CoverPage.html">HTML
3.0</A><BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The cover page to a hypertext document giving the specifications
for HTML version 3.

</BLOCKQUOTE><P>

<img src="NEW_TINY.GIF"><a 
href="http://www.w3.org/pub/WWW/MarkUp/Wilbur">HTML 3.2 at a glance</a><br>
<blockquote>Fresh from the presses of the World Wide Web Consortium, here 
is an overview of the latest specifications of the latest "official" 
version of HTML (relief for those of us who were wondering which way 
Netscape was going to go and which way Microsoft was going to 
go).</blockquote><p>

<A href="http://home.netscape.com/assist/net_sites/index.html">Netscape's
General Information Site</A><BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A good general site for documentation, editors, and instruction
about HTML. There are some good utilities here, under "Developers' Tools,"
including GIF converters, and MapEdit and WebMap (two handy utilities for
creating image-maps).

</BLOCKQUOTE><P><A HREF=http://www.iconovex.com/ISOCHART.HTM>Character
Chart</A><BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>This is a rather handy table that gives the HTML code values
for a number of slightly non-standard ASCII characters (you never know when
you might want to include a &#165;, a &reg;, or a &Ccedil; in your document).

</BLOCKQUOTE><P><A name="3"></A>

<H2>HTML Tools

</H2><P><EM>Converters, editors, viewers, and the like.</EM>

<P>

<P><A href="http://www.yahoo.com/Computers/World_Wide_Web/HTML_Editors/MS_Windows/">HTML
Editors</A><BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A nice collection of HTML editors for many platforms, and more
links to other collections.

</BLOCKQUOTE><P><A
href="http://WWW.Stars.com/Vlib/Providers/HTML_Editors.html">Windows
Editors</A><BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A collection of HTML editors specifically for Windows, from The
Web Developer's Virtual Library. Most are shareware or freeware.

</BLOCKQUOTE><P>

<A href="http://www.microsoft.com/msoffice/freestuf/msword/download/ia/ia1z/default.htm">
Microsoft's Internet Assistant for Word 6.0a&reg; </A>

<BLOCKQUOTE>This is Microsoft's addition for MS Word&reg; , turning it into
an HTML browser/editor. You do need Word 6.0a, but if you only have 6.0,
this page also can lead you to the patch/upgrade program for 6.0a. Be warned:
this site can be hard to get to; you may get mysterious error messages that
are simply roundabout ways of saying "too busy, try later."

</BLOCKQUOTE><P>
<A href="http://wp.novell.com/elecpub/inttoc.htm">Internet Publisher for
WordPerfect for Windows&reg; 6.1</A>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Not to be outdone, Novell has released Internet Publisher, which
allows
you to view and edit HTML files in WordPerfect for Windows (although you
may have to deal with WP's new "Envoy" format as an interim step).

</BLOCKQUOTE><P>


<P><A href="http://www.yahoo.com/Computers/World_Wide_Web/HTML_Converters/">A
Collection of Converters at the Yahoo site</A>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A large collection of programs useful for converting documents
from many different sources into HTML documents. Yahoo is also an excellent
starting point for general Web browsing.

</BLOCKQUOTE><P><A HREF=http://www.iconovex.com/HTMLCON.ZIP>HTMLCON.ZIP</A>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A simple DOS utility that can change HTML files into straight
ASCII text; this can be useful, as most Web Browsers only allow you to save
documents in HTML form.

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<a href="http://www.tucows.com/">Ultimate Collection of Winsock Software</a>
<BLOCKQUOTE>As the name might suggest, a sizeable collection of Winsock 
utilities.  Lots of good shareware related to web browsing and 
creating/enhancing HTML.
</BLOCKQUOTE>


<H2><A name="4">HTML Discussion Groups and Style Guides</A>

</H2><P><EM>Newsgroups, discussion centers, the IETF (Internet Engineering
Task Force).</EM>

<P><A href="http://www.ics.uci.edu/pub/ietf/html">The IETF HTML Working
Page</A>

<BLOCKQUOTE>These are some of the people who determine Internet Protocols
and the way we see the Web. Here are a number of discussion documents, including
notes from their conferences.

</BLOCKQUOTE><P><A href="http://info.med.yale.edu/caim/StyleManual_Top.HTML">Web
Style Manual</A>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The Center for Advanced Instructional Media at Yale has put together
this manual for designing WWW pages. While it can offer a number of insights,
it is <U>not</U> an instruction manual for HTML (although the
<STRONG>resources</STRONG> link on this page can point you to such manuals).

</BLOCKQUOTE><P><A href="http://www.utoronto.ca/webdocs/HTMLdocs/NewHTML/intro.html">A
Manual of HTML</A>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A hyper-text book, in effect a comprehensive collection of documents,
of varying age, found at the University of Toronto. It covers many aspects
of HTML and writing solid HTML documents. Some good advice and also a nice
collection of helper applications and tools.

</BLOCKQUOTE><P><A href="http://oneworld.wa.com/htmldev/devpage/dev-page4.html">Papers
and Conferences</A><BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A collection of papers and conferences about HTML and the World
Wide Web in general. There's also a link back to OneWorld Information Services,
a nice jumping-off point for Web information and Web page development.

</BLOCKQUOTE><P>

<H2><A name="5">HTML Validators</A></h2>
<i>Sites that check your web pages, some just spellcheck, others make 
sure you're using good HTML code.  Note: most on-line validators are 
very strict and "literal-minded."  Sometimes they may tag 
something as "wrong," but it will still work, it just doesn't 
adhere perfectly to the rules of HTML.</i><p> 
<a href="http://www2.imagiware.com/RxHTML/">Dr. HTML</a>
<blockquote>A powerful on-line HTML validation site that allows you to 
type in a URL and then select the aspects of your web page that you wish to 
test (table structure, spelling, check the hyperlinks).</blockquote><p>

<a href="http://www.goldendome.net/Tools/WebSter/">WebSter's Dictionary</a>
<blockquote>Purely an on-line spellchecker, but a good one.  Just enter 
the URL of the page you want to check, and it generates a form 
with any suspect words, and suggestions for alternate spellings.</blockquote>
<p>



<HR>

