<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>AnchorPage ComputerUser Review</title></head><body>
<BLOCKQUOTE><h1>ComputerUser</h1><hr><h2><cite>Down to
Business</cite></h2><p>
<strong>Internet</strong>. Access software packs
such as <i>Chameleon</i> 4.5 from NetManage (408/973-7171),
<I>RUMBA for the Internet</i> from Wall Data (206/814-3660) and
<i>SuperTCP Pro</i> from Frontier Technologies Corp.
(800/929-3054) were everywhere. Lotus announced <i>InterNotes
Web Publisher</i> for converting <i>Notes</i> databases to Web
documents; Novell was showing its free <i>WordPerfect Internet
Publisher</i> and its <i>TUXEDO 5</I> electronic-commerce 
architecture. But here's the big news: MCI Communications
announced its vBNS (very high-speed Backbone Network Service),
linking five U.S. supercomputer centers via fiber optics at
many times the speed of the current NSFNet-based
Internet.<BR>CompuServe talked up its Web browser and The Israel
Forum, an international online community area. America Online
was flaunting its NaviPress and NaviServer offerings for
publishing on the Web.<BR><strong>But the really cool product in
this category is <i>AnchorPage</i> from ICONOVEX
(800/943-0292). Yes, the company that makes software for
automatic indexing of word-processing documents now has a
product that does automatic indexing and HTML conversions of
word-processing documents (so far just under <i>Windows
3.1</i>) into Web sites.</strong><br>(Emphasis
added - ed.)</BLOCKQUOTE><P><i>*Reprinted
with permission; June 1995 issue of <b>ComputerUser</b></i><P><hr>
