<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>PCWeek Review</title></head><body>
<BLOCKQUOTE><h1>PCWEEK</h1>The National Newspaper of
Corporate Computing<hr>February 27,
1995<p>
<h2>Web utility gives developers hand defining
links</h2><cite>By Lisa Nadile</cite><p>Adding hyperlinks to
documents is a tedious process. To help relieve this drudgery,
Iconovex Corp. is now shipping AnchorPage, an $895 tool that
automatically creates hypertext tags for Hypertext Markup
Language documents using the company's indexing and linguistic
technology.<br>&#160;&#160;AnchorPage analyzes a World Wide Web
server database and compiles any of four synopses using
phrases, abstracts, or concept-based searches, said officials 
from the Bloomington, Minn., company. These synopses, compiled
at a rate of about 300 words per second, contain entries based
on keywords or phrases similar to a book index, which is then
used to automatically create hyperlinks between elements of the
document.<br>&#160;&#160;<b>Web site administrators appreciated
the chance to more quickly create hyperlinks across large
documents.<br>&#160;&#160;"This will reduce hundreds of
man-hours for people with traditional text databases," said
Jeremy Allaire, president of New World Media Inc., in
Minneapolis. "The engine itself is also unique; all other
products only (compile using) keywords.</b> I'd like to see the
capability to search the indices by keyword added as well as
the ability to integrate the index's information into a relational
database." <br>(Emphasis added - ed.)</blockquote><p><hr><a
href="http:/HOMEPAGE.HTM"><img src="http:/ICONHOME.GIF"
alt="Return" align=middle> Return to the Iconovex
HomePage</a><p><address>August 25th, 1995 
cml@iconovex.com</address></body></html>
