<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>AnchorPage Press Release</title></head><body>
<h3>Initial Release</h3>
<H2><CENTER>AnchorPage</CENTER></H2>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<P>
<CENTER><H2>NEW SOFTWARE AUTOMATICALLY INSERTS HYPERTEXT ANCHORS
INTO DOCUMENTS FOR THE WEB</CENTER> </H2><P>
Bloomington, MN. ICONOVEX Corporation, the leader in automatic
indexing software, announces the release of <B>AnchorPage</B>,
an automatic hypertext anchoring program which inserts HTML tags
into document databases on the World Wide Web.<P>
AnchorPage's fast conceptual analysis of text documents produces
any or all of four synopses: Concept, Abstract and Phrase Pages,
as well as a Table of Contents Page. The entries within these
synopsis pages become &quot;hot words&quot; with automatic links
to the passages in the documents from which they were generated.
This hypertext linkage allows a reader to skim quickly through
any of the AnchorPage-generated synopses for items of interest
and to call up the pertinent document with the click of a mouse.<P>
&quot;AnchorPage will completely change the way information
is found on and accessed from Web servers by using conceptual navigation,
&quot; states Robert Griggs, Vice President of Sales and Marketing for
Iconovex. &quot;The current method involves manual insertion of HTML
tags on the part of a server administrator to create hypertext links.
Because of time constraints and the increasing volume of information posted
on servers, most documents have links only to their titles. AnchorPage
links you to the key phrases and concepts within those documents.&quot;
<P>
AnchorPage makes retrieving information on the World Wide Web
faster and more reliable. Once a Web site uses AnchorPage to link
all of its documents, users of that Web site will be able to view
synopsis pages of the documents they think may be relevant to
their search, retrieving them in a fraction of the time it would
take to download the entire document. They can scan the phrases,
concepts, abstracts or table of contents for relevant information,
and upon finding it, click on the appropriate entry and retrieve
the section of the document from which the entry was generated. 
<P>
&quot;AnchorPage's fully automatic HTML tag generation allows publishers
to post documents faster while keeping administrative overhead at a 
minimum,&qu$
states Sotomayor. &quot;Easy access to the most recent information
will make any Web site more profitable.&quot;
<P>
On the Web, one often finds home pages with vague or undifferentiated
titles in their list of contents. For example:
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<strong><I>Welcome to the Web</I>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>An Introduction to the Web</I>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>The Web First-Time User's Guide</I>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>Navigating the Web</I>
</BLOCKQUOTE></strong><P>
Faced with a selection like this, the user is forced to pick at
random, suffer a long wait for the document to be transferred,
and hope for the best. But on Web sites hyperlinked with AnchorPage,
the user will be able to quickly retrieve the synopsis pages of
the document in question and then decide whether the whole document
is worth retrieving.<P>
A Concept Page contains a document's key concepts rotated around
the most significant term in the concept, alphabetized according 
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>Navigating the Web</I>
to those significant terms. For example, a legal document processed
by AnchorPage contains the following entries on the Concept Page:<P>
<I><B>PROFIT</B></I><P><I>Limited royalties, working interests,
production payments, net <B>PROFIT</B> interests or other interests in
minerals or other natural resources</I><P>
<I>Personal <B>PROFIT</B> or advantage to affiliated or subsidiary
company or association being personal profit to corporate trustee</I>
<P><I><B>PROFIT</B> resulting from change in form of principal </I>
<P>Anchor Page is a Windows application that requires Microsoft Windows
3.1 or Windows for Workgroups 3.1 or later. It fully automates
concept extraction and hypertext anchoring of HTML documents and
requires 8 MB of RAM to function efficiently. It can create hypertext
links between documents (as between a home page and a document)
or between related entries within a document. The user can select
multiple documents to process at once and can choose any or all
four possible outputs: Table of contents, phrase page, concept
page, and abstract page. These four output forms can also be horizontally 
linked such that an entry in the phrase page can contain a hypertext
link to the related concept entry, which can also be linked to
the related abstract entry. This gives Web servers a full set
of options in designing the access and entry points to the documents
in their database.<P>
AnchorPage joins the ICONOVEX product line which includes: Syntactica,
the core technology, available for developers in an API. Syntactica's
linguistic analysis is the basis for the AnchorPage program. Indexicon
is ICONOVEX's automatic indexing software program for word processors,
and finally LexEdit, an add on tool that allows users to create
personal word lists for Indexicon.<P>
AnchorPage sells for $895 and is available direct by calling ICONOVEX
Corporation at 800-943-0292, accessing their Web site at 
http://www.iconovex.co$
or through e-mail at Compuserve 74064,440. Technical inquiries
and product information requests may be directed to the above
numbers or to ICONOVEX Corporation at 7900 Xerxes Ave. South, Suite 550,
Bloomington, MN 55431.<P>
ICONOVEX Corporation is a software development company and a wholly-owned
subsidiary of INNOVEX, Inc., the world's leading manufacturer
of lead-wire assemblies for the thin film disk drive market.
<p>

