<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>EchoSearch Release Notes</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<!-- RTFact 1.3 Iconovex Corporation 1995 -->

<BODY bgcolor="FFCC99">
<center><h1>EchoSearch Release Notes</h1></center>
<hr>
<center><b><br>Check out what's new for latest version of
EchoSearch! <br>Or see what has been updated, added, or fixed in previous
releases.</b></center><br>

<BR><BR><BR>
<h2>Release Notes for Version 1.07</h2>

<h3>Added Features</h3>
<ol>
<li>Automatic detection of proxy information.

Proxy server information is now automatically detected from the system
registry and applied in the Network Settings dialog (Options menu).  A
"Defaults" button has been added to this dialog that can be used to get
the proxy information from the default browser.

<li>Search engines can now be cloned.

Using the clone feature, other versions of a supported search engine type
can be added to EchoSearch, for example, an Intranet or European version
of a search engine.  At this time, only AltaVista can be cloned.
EchoSearch includes three AltaVista clones: US, Australia, and Europe.
</ol>

<h3>Bug Fixes</h3>
<ol>

<li>Due to an increased number of problems reported with EchoSearch 1.06,
which used the Java Just In Time (JIT) compiler, we have switched back
to Sun's regular Java runtime.
</ol>

<h3>Online Services</h3>
EchoSearch will not work with any online services that do NOT support a
32-bit winsock (WSOCK32.DLL).  Services such as AOL and Prodigy are
currently working on 32-bit support.  Services that allow the use of a
32-bit winsock, such as Netcom and CompuServe, will run EchoSearch without
difficulty.  For additional information on using EchoSearch with these
type of services, see the CONNECT.TXT file.
<h3>Known Problems</h3>
<b><i>Web Browsers:</b></i><br>
Only 32-bit browsers are capable of supporting the long filenames used by
EchoSearch.  We recommend using Netscape 2.0 or better or Internet Explorer
3.0 or better to view EchoSearch search results.
<P>
<b><i>Spamdexing:</b></i>           <br>
In an effort to increase the likelihood that a document will be considered
a &quot;hit&quot; by search engines, some Webmasters may include text that
has
nothing but keywords repeated over and over again.  When an author has
used this method of attracting search engines, coined &quot;spamdexing,
&quot; you will often find strange entries in the Concept view and Qualified Results
where a word or phrase is repeated over and over.  If you then click on
one of these entries, you may jump to a paragraph that is unrelated to the
entry or to an &quot;empty&quot; paragraph, because the original text was
hidden by the author so that it would not be visible in a browser (to locate the
entry in the original document, use the &quot;View Source&quot; or similar
option to view the HTML source and then use the &quot;Find&quot; feature, often CTRL +
F).
<P>
While we do our best to filter out this kind of material, we cannot filter
it out completely without the risk of eliminating truly valid index entries
contained in spamdexed documents.
<p>
Sometimes authors may include spamdexing in
 the title of the document. In such cases the summary view will display the
 titles as the author has written them.
<P>
<b><i>Netscape Navigator 2.0 With Windows NT:</b></i>    <br>
When Windows NT users are running EchoSearch with Netscape 2.0 minimized
or in the background, the Netscape 2.0 window will not automatically
become the active window after EchoSearch has finished processing; users
must manually select the Netscape window.  Windows 95 users will not
experience this problem.  This problem will not occur for Windows NT
users if they are using Netscape Navigator 2.01.
<P>
<b><i>Entering Invalid Searches:</b></i>                     <br>
EchoSearch does not do any semantic testing of search queries to ensure
that they are valid.  You could, for instance, enter a query which
specified both that &quot;motorcycles&quot; must be included and that &quot;
motorcycles&quot;
must not be included.
<P>
<b><i>Uninstall Leaves Remnants:</b></i><br>
The uninstall program will occassionally be unable to remove the java
folder and will therefore leave the iconovex\java directory intact.  You
can remove this directory manually from the DOS prompt or reboot the
computer and re-run the uninstall program.
<P>
<b><i>Unvisited Links Appear Visited:</b></i> <br>
Because EchoSearch uses the same filenames for each run, it is possible
that on your second or third query in the same session you will begin to
see links marked as &quot;visited&quot; that you know you haven't yet
clicked on.
<P>
If this becomes a problem, you can probably clear the visited links
through your browser.  For instance, in Netscape Navigator, choose
Options-&gt;General Preferences-&gt;Appearance and click on the &quot;Expire
now&quot;
button.

<BR><BR>
<hr>
<h4><b>If this is the first version of EchoSearch you have used,
please read the release notes below for previous versions of
EchoSearch.</h4></b>
<hr>
<BR><BR>

<h2>Release Notes for Version 1.06</h2>

<h3>Added Features</h3>
<ol>
<li>Searches can now be performed based on speed or based on relevance.  The
default is "speed."  Using this option, hits will be collected as they
are returned from the search engines, regardless of how each search engine
has rated the hits.  With the speed option, you will obtain more hits
from the faster search engines and you may get different results when
running the same query at another time.  Using the relevance option,
EchoSearch will divide the number of hits you requested among all the
engines to obtain an approximately equal number of hits from each engine.
With the relevance option, it will take longer to collect hits, because
EchoSearch will wait for the slower engines to "connect" and return their
hits.
<li>Automatic detection of registered browser. When EchoSearch is run for the
first time, it will look in the Windows registry for the name and the
location of the registered browser. This will be displayed in the Select
Browser dialog.
<li>Just-in-Time compiler.  EchoSearch now ships with the Java Just-in-Time
(JIT) compiler.  This should improve the overall speed of EchoSearch.
<li>Document descriptions now include the size and the date (if available)
of the document, as provided by each search engine.</ol>
<h3>Bug Fixes</h3>
<ol>
<li>The installation program now installs mfc30.dll in the
Iconovex\java\bin directory. This will fix the problem for NT 4.0 users.
<li>Framed documents are now handled properly.
<li>Kernel32.dll update.  Microsoft has released a Kernel32.dll update for
Windows 95 that resolves a memory leak which occurs when opening and
closing a Socket using the Windows Sockets API.  If you are getting
GPFs or IPFs when running EchoSearch, it may be because of this memory
leak.  See the online help for more information on obtaining this update.
</ol>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
