<HEAD>
<TITLE>Online Service Providers</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFCC99">

<h3><center>INSTRUCTIONS FOR USING ECHOSEARCH WITH ONLINE SERVICE
PROVIDERS</h3></center>
<hr>

Included in this file:
<P>
*<A HREF="#aol"> America Online</a><br>
*<a href="#cserve"> CompuServe</a><br>
*<a href="#msn"> Microsoft Network (MSN)</a><br>
*<a href="#net"> Netcom/Netcruiser </a><br>
*<a href="#prod"> Prodigy</a><br>
*<a href="#spry"> Sprynet</a><br>
*<a href="#auto"> Opening an Internet Connection to your ISP Automatically in
Windows 95</a><br>
* <a href="#trouble">Troubleshooting</a><br>
* <a href="#contact">Contact Information for Internet Service
Providers</a>

<P>


<b>DISCLAIMER:</b> The instructions in this file are provided as a courtesy
to EchoSearch users.  Iconovex is not liable for any damages suffered
as a result of using or modifying these instructions.
<P>

<b>A NOTE ABOUT INTERNET SERVICE PROVIDERS:</b> You must be able to connect
to the Internet using the Windows 32-bit winsock, WSOCK32.DLL. If you attempt
to use EchoSearch with a 16-bit connection, EchoSearch will either display
an error when it trys to update the search engine drivers and connect to
the search engines or it will only be able to connect to one search
engine (and will eventually not work at all).  If you need help beyond
the instructions provided in this file, please contact your ISP (see
<a href="#contact">Contact Information</a>).
<p>
<b>A NOTE ABOUT BROWSERS:</b> In order to view EchoSearch output, you will
need a browser that supports long filenames, e.g., Internet Explorer (version
3.0 or greater recommended) or the 32-bit version of Netscape Navigator
(version 3.0 or greater recommended). The default browsers distributed with
many online services *do not* currently support long filenames. If your
provider does not use a 32-bit browser, you will need to obtain Internet
Explorer or the 32-bit Netscape to use with EchoSearch. You can still use
the default browser for your other Internet activities if you are using
these online services.  If you need help beyond the instructions provided
in this file, please contact your ISP (see <a href="#contact">Contact
Information</a>). <P>

==============================================================

<a name="aol"><h3>America Online</h3>

<P>
America Online has released the 32-bit/Windows 95 version 3.0 of its
software, which includes Internet Explorer 3.0.  Version 3.0 for Windows
3.1 will NOT work with EchoSearch.
<p>
<center>      Instructions for Using EchoSearch with America Online 3.0
<p>    -------------------------------------------------------------
</center>
<p>
In order to run EchoSearch with America Online, you will need to open
and "connect" to America Online BEFORE you begin a search. EchoSearch
will use this connection to perform its searches.  While you can perform
other activities online while EchoSearch is running, be aware that this may
slow EchoSearch's searching and processing speed. Also remember that
EchoSearch will not automatically close your connection to America Online
when you close EchoSearch.
<P>

==============================================================

<a name="cserve"><h3>CompuServe</h3>

<P>
CompuServe is now shipping version 3.0.1 for Windows 95 of their
software. Internet Explorer 3.0 is also included.  Version 3.0.1 for
Windows 3.1 will NOT work with EchoSearch.
<p>

<center>        Instructions for Using EchoSearch with CompuServe 3.0.1
<p>    -------------------------------------------------------------
</center>
<p>
In order to run EchoSearch with CompuServe, you will need to open and
"connect" to CompuServe BEFORE you begin a search. EchoSearch will use
this connection to perform its searches. While you can perform other
activities online while EchoSearch is running, be aware that this may slow
EchoSearch's searching and processing speed. Also remember that EchoSearch
will not automatically close your connection to CompuServe when you close
EchoSearch.
<p>
 <center><h4>Instructions for Using Windows 95 and CompuServe 2.01
 </center></h4>
<p>
If you have not yet received the new version and you are using Windows 95,
you can set up a dial-up connection to CompuServe, using the Windows 95
dialer. See the instructions below. You will also need to obtain a copy
of Internet Explorer or Netscape in order to view EchoSearch output.
<p>
 The following instructions are a variance of two
posts made on a CompuServe forum (CIMNETMO.TXT, submitted by Robin Johansen,
and CIMNET3.TXT, submitted by Marcel Farge).

<P> <P> <b><center>READ THESE
NOTES BEFORE YOU START ANYTHING!!!</b></center> <P>

<b>NOTE 1:</b>
<P>
This document assumes that you already have WinCim 2.0.1 on a PC using
Windows 95 and that you wish to install Netscape as an alternate Internet
browser using CompuServe as the service provider. It also assumes that you
have installed the Internet Jumpstart kit available on Microsoft PLUS and
that you have run the &quot;Internet Setup Wizard&quot; which this install
provides.
<P>

<b>NOTE 2:</b>
<P>
For experienced Windows 95 users who have not already installed the
Internet Jumpstart kit from Microsoft PLUS, you can save yourself some
time and aggravation in having to install the required system elements
in a piecemeal fashion by making sure that you have the following on
your system. These elements can be added using the &quot;Add/Remove Programs
facility in Control Panel:
<P>
* Dial-up Adaptor<br>
* TCP/IP<br>
* Dial-up Scripting Tool<br>
* Client for Microsoft Windows<br>
<P>
<b>NOTE 3:</b>
<P>
As an alternative to installing software from Microsoft PLUS -
Microsoft's Internet Explorer can be downloaded FREE (GO WINCON) as
MSIE20.EXE.  This file contains the Internet Explorer AND the Internet
Jumpstart Kit - with Internet Setup Wizard (i.e., &quot;Internet Tools&quot;).
Running MSIE20.EXE will install all of this. CAUTION - Internet Explorer
*might* cause a problem - see Section G below - &quot;ANOTHER PROBLEM
SOMETIMES ENCOUNTERED&quot;.
<P>
As of 8/2/96, there is a beta version of Internet Explorer 3.0, however,
these instructions have not been tested with that version.
<p>
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
<P>
<h3>SECTION A</h3>
<P>
<b>FIRST STEPS</b>
<P>
Before setting up the Win95 dialer, watch for two traps:
<P>
<b>TRAP # 1:</b> Multiple winsocks
<P>
Unfortunately there are several winsock.dll files about which are not
all equal - you must sort this out as follows:
<P>

1). Open Windows Explorer<br>
2). Highlight &quot;My Computer&quot;<br>
3). Click on &quot;Tools&quot; - Click on &quot;Find&quot; - Click on &quot;
Files or Folders...&quot;<br>
4). In the &quot;Named&quot; box enter &quot;winsock.dll&quot; (without
quotation marks)<br>
5). Check &quot;Include subfolders&quot;<br>
6). Click &quot;Find Now&quot;<br>
<P>
This will tell you what winsock.dll files you have installed.
<P>
You MUST HAVE the winsock.dll (133K dated 11/28/95) in X:\CSERVE\WINCIM,
X:\CSERVE\MOSAIC, and X:\CSERVE\CID where &quot;X&quot; is the drive on
which you have your CompuServe stuff installed.
<P>
It is probably NOT a good idea to have these folders in the &quot;PATH&quot;
statement in your AUTOEXEC.BAT file (usually found in C:\)
<P>
<b>#### REMOVE OR RENAME ALL OTHER WINSOCK.DLL FILES ####</b>
<P>
Repeat steps 1 thru 6 above but substitute &quot;winsock.dll&quot; with
&quot;wsock32.dll&quot; in step 4. You should find wsock32.dll (65K 07/11/95)
in both your X:\WINDOWS &amp; X:\WINDOWS\SYSTEM folders.
<P>
<b>TRAP #2:</b> 16-bit vs. 32-bit Netscapes
<P>
There are two variants of Netscape 2 - 16 bit and 32 bit.  The one you
need is the 32 bit.  Their are several 32-bit versions available titled
&quot;N32E201.EXE&quot; OR &quot;ATLS32S2.EXE&quot; - both will work OK.  It
is assumed that you already know how to install this. If not see the instructions at
http://www.netscape.com.
<P>

^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
<P>

<h3>SECTION B</h3>
<P>

<b>WIN95 DIALER</b>
<P>

1). Click on &quot;Start&quot; and click on &quot;Settings&quot; and &quot;
Control Panel.&quot;  Then double-click on the Network icon.  You should see &quot;Dial-up Adapter
&quot; and &quot;TCP/IP&quot; and &quot;Client for Microsoft Windows&quot; under &quot;
The following network components are installed.&quot;
<P>

If not, install them as follows:
<P>
* (In the Network dialog), click on the Add button and a new
menu will appear.  To install &quot;TCP/IP,&quot; select &quot;Protocol,
&quot; and click the Add button. This will bring up the Select Network
Protocol dialog.  Choose &quot;Microsoft&quot; from the Manufacturers
list and &quot;TCP/IP&quot; from the Network Protocols list. Click OK.
<P>
* To install &quot;Dial-up Adapter&quot;, click the Add button.  Select
&quot;Adapter,&quot; and click Add button.  Choose &quot;Microsoft&quot;
from the Manufacturers list and select Dial-up Adapter.  Click OK.
<P>

2). (In the Network dialog) Select &quot;TCP/IP&quot; click &quot;
Properties.&quot;  Click on the IP Address tab and choose &quot;Obtain an IP address automatically.
&quot; Click on the Bindings tab.  &quot;Client for Microsoft Windows&quot; should
be checked.  Then choose the DNS Configuration tab.  Make sure &quot;Disable
DNS&quot; is chosen.  Then chose the &quot;WINS Configuration&quot; tab and
choose &quot;Use DHCP for WINS Resolution.&quot;  Click on OK and OK again to exit.  You will
then be asked to reboot your computer.
<P>
3). You will now need to configure Dial-up Networking to connect to
CompuServe.  Double-click on the My Computer icon on your desktop.  First
double-click on the Modems icon and make sure you have set up your modem.
Also see if there is a Dial-up Networking icon.  (If it isn't you can
install it using the &quot;Add/Remove Programs&quot; facility in the Control
Panel.)
<P>
Double-click the &quot;Dial-up networking&quot; folder and choose &quot;Make
New Connection.&quot;  Give your Connection a name (e.g, &quot;CompuServe&quot;)
.
<P>
4). Click &quot;Configure&quot; to set up your modem.
<P>
On the &quot;General&quot; tab:<br>
Select the appropriate Communications Port for your modem.<br>
Select Speaker volume to your personal preference level.<br>
Select &quot;Maximum speed.&quot;  Use 19200 if using a 14,400 modem.  Use
38400 if you are using a 28,800 modem connecting to a 28,800 CIS
phone line.<br>
Leave the &quot;Only connect at this speed&quot; box unchecked.<br>
<P>
Click on &quot;Connection&quot; tab:<br>
Set &quot;Databits&quot; to 8, &quot;Parity&quot; to none, and &quot;Stop
bits&quot; to 1.<br>
Check &quot;Wait for dial tone before dialing.&quot;<br>
Check &quot;Cancel call if not connected within 60 secs.&quot;<br>
<P>
Click the Port Settings Button.  Check &quot;Use FIFO buffers (requires
16550 compatible UART).&quot;
<P>

=======================================================================
<b>**NOTE** SOME FORUM MEMBERS REPORT THAT UNCHECKING THIS FIXES A PROBLEM
WHEN THE DIALER FAILS TO ESTABLISH A CONNECTION [I.E., THEY PROBABLY DO
NOT HAVE A 16550 UART].</b>
=======================================================================
<P>
Set the &quot;Receive Buffer&quot; slider at the third mark from the left.<br>
Set the &quot;Transmit Buffer&quot; slider at the hard right position.<br>
Click OK.<br>
<P>
Click the Advanced button.<br>
Check &quot;Use error control,&quot; &quot;Compress data,&quot; &quot;Use
flow control,&quot; and &quot;Hardware (RTS/CTS).&quot;  Set &quot;Modulation type&quot; to
Standard.<br>
Click OK.<br>
<P>
Click on the &quot;Options&quot; tab:<br>
Make sure that in the Connection Control area, NEITHER OPTION IS
SELECTED.<br>
Click OK.<br>
<P>
5). Click &quot;Next&quot; and enter your CompuServe access phone number.
<P>
6). Click &quot;Next,&quot; check the details, and click &quot;Finish.&quot;
<P>
7). In the Dial-up Networking folder, highlight your new connection
(i.e., the one now labeled &quot;CompuServe&quot;) with the left mouse
button and then press the right mouse button and select &quot;Properties.&quot;
<P>
Choose &quot;Server type.&quot;  On the &quot;Type of Dial-up Server:&quot;
click on the arrow and choose &quot;PPP:Windows 95, Windows NT 3.5, Internet.&quot;  The
only box that should be checked on this page should be &quot;TCP/IP.&quot;
<P>
Select &quot;TCP/IP.&quot;  Choose &quot;Server assigned IP Address,&quot;
and choose &quot;Specify name server addresses.&quot;  In Primary  DNS, type in
149.174.211.5. Secondary DNS should be 149.174.213.5.  Choose &quot;Use IP header
compression&quot; and choose &quot;Use default gateway on remote network.
&quot;  Then click OK, OK, and OK again.
<P>
8). You are now ready to set up scripting.
<P>
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
<P>
<h3>SECTION C</h3>
<P>
<b>SCRIPTING</b>
<P>
<b>#######-VERY IMPORTANT POINT FOLLOWS-################</b>
PLEASE NOTE THAT THIS SCRIPT WORKS ONLY FOR DIRECT COMPUSERVE DIAL-UP.
IF YOU USE ANOTHER PROVIDER TO CONNECT TO COMPUSERVE THIS MAY NOT WORK.
E.g., IF YOU USE FT Connect OR SIMILAR THIS IS PROBABLY NOT THE SCRIPT
FOR YOU.
<P>
If you are unsure whether you access CompuServe direct, in WinCim, click
&quot;Special&quot; and then click &quot;Session Settings.&quot;  If the the
entry in the &quot;Network&quot; box is not &quot;CompuServe,&quot; this script WILL
PROBABLY NOT WORK!!!!
<P>
There is an EXCELLENT shareware product called FINDCIS.EXE which has
phone numbers AND service provider details for THE WHOLE WORLD if you
want to find your nearest DIRECT COMPUSERVE phone number. You can find
this product at GO SPFORUM, GO EURFORUM and GO INETFR.
<b>###################################################</b>
<P>
<b>-----The Script------</b>
<P>
Use the Edit function of the program you are using to view this file to
copy all the stuff immediately below here beginning with the semi-colon
and ending with &quot;endproc.&quot;  Paste this into Notepad or Wordpad and
then save the file as CIS.SCP in ASCII text file format in your
C:\Program Files\Accessories folder.
<P>
=======================================================================
<P>
;<br>
; This script establishes a PPP connection with CompuServe. This requires
; changing the port settings to log in.<br>
; <br>
; <br>
; Main entry point to script<br>
;                           <br>
proc main                   <br>
;                           <br>
; Set the port settings so we can wait for non-gibberish text.<br>
;<br>
set port databits 7<br>
set port parity even<br>
;<br>
transmit &quot;^M&quot;<br>
;<br>
waitfor &quot;Host Name:&quot;<br>
transmit &quot;CIS^M&quot;    <br>
;<br>
waitfor &quot;User ID:&quot;<br>
transmit $USERID<br>
transmit &quot;/go:pppconnect^M&quot;<br>
;<br>
waitfor &quot;Password:&quot;<br>
transmit $PASSWORD<br>
transmit &quot;^M&quot;<br>
;<br>
waitfor &quot;One moment please...&quot;<br>
;<br>
; Set the port settings back to allow successful<br>
; negotiation.<br>
;<br>
set port databits 8<br>
set port parity none<br>
;<br>
endproc<br>
<P>
=======================================================================
<P>
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
<P>
 <h3>SECTION D:</h3>
<P>
<b>DIAL-UP SCRIPTING TOOL</b>
<P>
1). Press the Start button, select &quot;Programs,&quot; then &quot;
Accessories.&quot;  If the Dial-Up Scripting Tool shows up, you're ready to proceed.
<P>
<b>*</b>If it is not there:<br>
(i) If you have the Windows 95 CD, press the Start button,
select &quot;Settings,&quot; then &quot;Control Panel.&quot;  Double-click
on the Add/Remove Programs icon.  Select the &quot;Windows Setup&quot; tab, then
click on the &quot;Have Disk&quot; option.  Assuming your CD-ROM drive is
D:, enter the path D:\Admin\Apptools\Dscript.  Click OK and the
SLIP/CSLIP drivers and Dial-up Scripting Tool will be installed.
<P>
(ii) If you have Windows 95 on floppies, you can download the
Dial-up Scripting Tool and SLIP drivers {DSCRPT.EXE} from the
Internet Resources Forum library on CompuServe via GO INETRES.
Run this file to extract the archive and then install as per the
readme file.]
<P>
2). Click Dial-Up Scripting Tool. You will see the utility's dialog box.
<P>
Your current dial-up profile(s) will be listed in the text area on the
left.
<P>
3). Select the profile for which you wrote the script, (&quot;CompuServe,
&quot; if you followed the example) and then click &quot;Browse.&quot;  If you saved
CIS.SCP in the C:\Program Files\Accessories folder, it should appear in the
dialog box. Select it and click &quot;Open.&quot;
<P>
4). Leave &quot;Step through script&quot; and &quot;Start terminal screen
minimized&quot; unchecked.  Click &quot;Apply&quot; and then click OK to close the Dial-up
Scripting Tool.
<P>
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
<P>
<h3>SECTION E:</h3>
<P>
<b>TO CONNECT YOUR SCRIPT</b>
<P>
In the Dial-Up Networking group, double-click on your dial-up networking
icon titled &quot;CompuServe&quot; (if you used the example) and enter your
username (e.g., 111111,2222) and password in the dialog boxes, since
your script will need these variables to connect.  It is assumed that
you can enter &quot;Dial-Up Properties...&quot; with no problem (the phone
number is of course that which you use to access CompuServe).
<P>
To test your work so far, click &quot;Connect&quot; and the dialer should
start initializing the modem and dialing.  You will know that you have been
successful when you see the &quot;Connected to CompuServe&quot; window pop
up and start counting time.  Do not panic if it takes a while to connect after
the popup window displays &quot;Password:&quot; and the following line with
a square &quot;bullet point.&quot;  This can take 30 seconds or so to process
the log-on and go to the next step.
<P>
Note that the connection speed is also displayed in the pop-up window,
e.g., 26400bps. The speed is not necessarily the speed of your modem; it
is determined at the time of connection by a number of factors.  If all
goes well with your connection click &quot;Disconnect&quot; and proceed with
Section F - if you are experiencing difficulty go to Section G.
<P>
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
<P>

<h3>SECTION F:</h3>
<P>
<b>ESTABLISHING THE LINK TO THE DIALER FROM NETSCAPE</b>
<P>
1). Click Start and select &quot;Settings&quot; and &quot;Control Panel.
&quot;<br>
2). Double-click on the icon &quot;Internet&quot; (If this is not present
see NOTE 3a below).<br>
3). On the &quot;Options&quot; tab, check &quot;Autodial&quot; and select
&quot;CompuServe&quot; as your dial-up network setting.<br>
4). Click OK.<br>
<P>
This should give you &quot;semi-automatic&quot; dialing so when you start
Netscape, a popup window will appear requiring you to click &quot;Connect.
&quot; The dialer should then connect you to CompuServe as your Internet
service provider.
<P>
You may want to adjust your preferences in Netscape:
<P>
1). Open Netscape.<br>
2). Click &quot;Options.&quot;<br>
3). Click &quot;Mail and News preferences.&quot;<br>
4). Click &quot;Servers&quot; tab.<br>
5). Set Outgoing Mail [SMTP] server = mail.compuserve.com.<br>
6). Set News [NNTP] Server = news.compuserve.com and News RC Directory =
X:\NETSCAPE\NEWS, where X = the drive where you have Netscape.<br>
7). Click &quot;Identity&quot; tab.<br>
8). Enter your name, email address, and reply address (usually your
email address).<br>
<P>
Your Name = John Smith<br>
Your Email = 111111.1111@compuserve.com<br>
Reply to Address = 111111.1111@compuserve.com<br>
<P>
<b>NOTE 1a</b> - DO NOT put a comma in your CompuServe address.  It is supposed
to be a stop, exactly as above.
<P>
<b>NOTE 2a</b> - You CAN NOT use Netscape mail to receive your CompuServe mail
because they do not have a POP3 server.  Sending mail is OK.
<P>
<b>NOTE 3a</b> - If you don't have the &quot;Internet&quot; icon (i.e., you have
not installed &quot;Internet tools&quot; as per notes 1 through 3 at the head of
this file) all is not lost.  You will just have to use &quot;Manual start up.
&quot; To do this &quot;fire up&quot; your dialer, and when you are connected to
CompuServe open Netscape.
<P>
<b>NOTE 4a</b> - The dialer DOES NOT DISCONNECT AUTOMATICALLY when you exit
Netscape.  You will HAVE TO manually disconnect the dialer when you
are finished.  To disconnect the dialer, click the Disconnect button
in the &quot;Connected To&quot; window.
<P>
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
<P>
<h3>SECTION G:</h3>
<P>
<b>ANOTHER PROBLEM SOMETIMES ENCOUNTERED</b>
<P>
<b>THE PROBLEM:</b> Dialer starts OK and establishes a connection.  Netscape is
started but just sits for what seems an eternity and eventually returns
the following error message:<br>
<p>
&quot;Netscape is unable to locate the server<br>
www.xxxxxxxx.com<br>
The server does not have a DNS entry<br>
Check the server name in the location [URL] and try again&quot;<br>
<P>
<b>OTHER SYMPTOMS:</b> Microsoft Explorer [also installed] behaves perfectly.
<P>
<b>A POSSIBLE FIX:</b> Remove the Internet stuff from WIN 95 using &quot;Add/Remove
Programs&quot; and then re-install Microsoft Internet Explorer by
downloading &quot;MSIE20.EXE&quot; as outlined at the start of this file (GO
WINCON).  Then run MSIE20.EXE, not using the Add/Remove Programs utility.
<P>
<b>ALSO CHECK:</b> Go to the Control Panel and double-click on &quot;Network.&quot;
Highlight &quot;Dial-up adapter&quot; and click &quot;Properties.&quot;  On
the Bindings tab you should only have ONE ENTRY, &quot;TCP/IP.&quot;
<P>
-------------------------------------------------------------
<P>
==============================================================
<a name="msn"><h3>Microsoft Network</h3>
<P>

EchoSearch will work using a connection to the Microsoft Network.
<p>
<center>       Instructions for EchoSearch with The Microsoft Network
<p>    -------------------------------------------------------------
</center>
<p>In order to run EchoSearch with the Microsoft Network, you will need
to open and "connect" to the Microsoft Network BEFORE you begin a
search. EchoSearch will use this connection to perform its searches.
While you can perform other activities online while EchoSearch is
running, be aware that this may slow EchoSearch's searching and
processing speed. Also remember that EchoSearch will not automatically
close your connection to the Microsoft Network when you close EchoSearch.

<P>
==============================================================
<a name="net"><h3>Netcom/Netcruiser Accounts</h3>
<p>
There are a few different kinds of Internet access accounts available
through Netcom.  There are some accounts that allow you to
choose which browser you want to use with that account.  There is also an
account called Netcruiser where you must use Netcom's proprietary browser,
Netcruiser, in order to surf the Internet.  Almost all of
Netcom's Internet access accounts will work with EchoSearch if configured
correctly with Windows 95 Dial-Up Networking. <p> If your Netcom account uses
a 16-bit Netcruiser browser or uses another browser that is not 32-bit,
Netcom has a Technical Support Web page that explains how to set up <a
href="http://www.netcom.com/bin/webtech/Other_Dialers_and_Operating_Systems/Dialers/win95.dial.html">Dial-Up Networking</a> and how to use 3rd party dialers with <a
href="http://www.netcom.com/bin/webtech/NETCOMplete/NetCruiser2.x/Common_Questions/win95.dial.html">Netcruiser</a> accounts. <p> <p><center>        Instructions for EchoSearch with Netcom <p>
------------------------------------------------------------- </center><p> In
order to run EchoSearch with Netcom, you will need to open and "connect" to
Netcom BEFORE you begin a search. EchoSearch will use this connection to
perform its searches. While you can perform other activities online while
EchoSearch is running, be aware that this may slow EchoSearch's searching and
processing speed. Also remember that EchoSearch will not automatically close
your connection to Netcom when you close EchoSearch. <p>

==============================================================
<a name="prod"><h3>Prodigy</h3>
<p>
Prodigy Internet for Windows 95 (only) has been released and includes
Netscape 3.0.  You can download this software from their
<a href="http://www.prodigy.com">Web site</a>.  This software has
NOT been tested with EchoSearch.
<P>
==============================================================
<a name="spry"><h3>Sprynet</h3>
<P>
You must set up a Dial-Up Networking connection to use Sprynet with
EchoSearch.  Instructions for setting up a Windows 95 dial-up connection to
Sprynet are provided
<a href="http://www.sprynet.com/members/techs/techtips.html">here</a>.
<p><center>           Instructions for Using EchoSearch with Sprynet
<P>    -------------------------------------------------------------
</center>
<p>In order to run EchoSearch with Sprynet, you will need to open and
"connect" to Sprynet BEFORE you begin a search. EchoSearch will use
this connection to perform its searches. While you can perform other
activities online while EchoSearch is running, be aware that this may slow
EchoSearch's searching and processing speed. Also remember that EchoSearch
will not automatically close your connection to Sprynet when you close
EchoSearch.
<P>
<a name="auto"></a>
==============================================================
<h3>Opening an Internet Connection to your Internet Service Provider
Automatically in Windows 95</h3>
<p>If you are using Dial-Up Networking (DUN) in Windows 95 to connect to your
Internet Service Provider, you *may* be able to open a connection to
your ISP automatically whenever an application requests an Internet
connection.  For some reason, this does not work with some DUN setups.
<p>
To do this:

<ol>
<li>Right-click on the Internet icon on your desktop and select Properties
(or double-click on this icon in Control Panel).

<li>On the "Options" tab, check "Autodial" and select your ISP from
the Dial-Up Networking drop-down list.

<li>Click OK.
</ol>
<p>This should give you "semi-automatic" dialing so when you start
EchoSearch, a popup window will appear requiring you to click "Connect."
The dialer should then connect you to your ISP.
<p>
==============================================================
<a name="trouble"><h3>Troubleshooting</h3>

<P>
<b>PROBLEM:</b> EchoSearch connects to the wrong service provider
<p>
<b>SOLUTION (Windows 95):</b> If you have multiple service providers set up on your
system (e.g., CompuServe and MSN), you may have another provider
set to establish your Internet connections.  Right-click on the
Internet icon on your desktop and select &quot;Properties&quot; (or open it
in the Control Panel).  On the Options tab, check &quot;Autodial,&quot; and
select the provider you want to use for your Internet connections.
<P>
<b>PROBLEM:</b> You get an error message "Error. Cannot connect to search
engines" when you try to run a search.

<p><b>SOLUTION:</b> You must be using Windows 95 or Windows NT.  EchoSearch
does not work on Windows 3.1.
<p>
<b>SOLUTION:</b> You must be using a 32-bit Internet connection in order to
run EchoSearch.  If you do not know if you are using a 32-bit connection,
check the information for your Internet Service Provider provided above,
or contact your ISP's Customer Service  or Technical Support
department (see "Contact Information" below).
<p>
<b>SOLUTION:</b> Check that you are using the correct username and password.
<p>
<b>SOLUTION:</b> Is your modem working correctly?  If it is an external modem,
is it on and plugged into a phone jack?
<p>
<b>SOLUTION:</b> Make sure that you are "connected" to your Internet Service
Provider.  You may also need to close and reopen EchoSearch if you
did not have a connection open before when you attempted to run a search.

<p>
<b>SOLUTION (Windows 95):</b> You may not have a 16550 compatible UART.  If you do not,
choose Start - Settings - Control Panel. Double-click on the Modems
icon.  Select your modem and click &quot;Properties.&quot;  Select the
Connection tab and &quot;Port Settings.&quot;  Uncheck the &quot;Use FIFO
buffers&quot; box.  Click OK, OK, and OK again to exit.

<p><b>PROBLEM: </b>Your browser is unable to find or display the search
results
<p>
<b>SOLUTION: </b>You must be using a 32-bit browser, which is able to display
files with long filenames, in order to view EchoSearch's search results.
If you do not know if you are using a 32-bit browser, check the
information for your Internet Service Provider provided above.  Or contact
your ISP's Customer Service or Technical Support department (see
<a href="#contact">Contact Information</a>) to find out how to obtain and set
up a 32-bit browser with your ISP's software.  We recommend that you use the
most current version of Netscape Navigator (3.0) or Internet Explorer (3.0).

<a name="contact"></a>
<p>==============================================================
<h3>Contact Information for Internet Service Providers</h3>
<p>
If need further help setting up your Internet Service Provider to work
with EchoSearch and/or need help obtaining and setting up a 32-bit
browser on your system, please contact your provider.
