<html>
<head><title>Columbia Daily Tribune Article</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<em>Article by Scott A. May, as seen in his <b>PC Solutions</b> column.
Reprinted with permission from the Columbia Daily Tribune</em>
<p>
Following years of empty promises and speculative ballyhoo, the information
age is finally upon us.  Your doorway to this brave new world is the personal
computer, linked globally via the Internet or internally through corporate
Intranets.  The trouble now is finding exactly what you need - quickly,
cheaply and effectively - in this growing  mountain of information.
<p>
The World Wide Web provides many tools, called search engines, to filter
through thousands of Internet sites.  Using a key word or phrase, these
engines search the entire Web and return "hit lists" relevant to your query.
Unfortunately, not all search engines are created equally.  It would be nice
to have a single tool that utilizes every search engine, while fine-tuning
your search criteria in ways no single engine allows.
<p>
Enter "EchoSearch from Iconovex Corp., experts in Web and network indexing
software.  Whether you search the web for fun or business research, consider
this one-stop window to the Net, guaranteed to save you time, trouble and
expense.
<p>
To use, the program requires an on-line access provider or direct link to a
corporate Intranet.  To begin, simply type in a word or phrase you wish to
search for.  Next, indicate where you want to search: the Web, Usenet or
Intranet.  Finally, specify the number of documents, or relevant "hits," that
you'd like returned.  Click the search button and the rest is automatic.
<p>
Web search engines supported by EchoSearch include AltaVista, Excite,
InfoSeek, Lycos, OpenText and WebCrawler.  Using special Java multi-threading
technology, the program submits your query to every search engine on the
list.  A progress screen shows which engine is being used and the number of
hits each generates.
<p>
When the searching process is complete, the program then downloads, analyzes
and indexes the results, which can then be viewed with your Web browser.
Here's the best part for those looking to save money: Only the actual search
process requires being on-line.  Setting up your query and viewing the
results are accomplished off-line.  No more wasted time and expense
conducting such research "live."
<p>
Search results are displayed in your browser in a number of different ways,
including an index view, concept view, summary view or search statistics.
Even though you're working off-line, you can still use many of your
browser's functions to find, print or bookmark source documents.  If you find
something of interest, simply click on that entry to go back on-line and
connect with that site.  Search results can also be saved to your hard disk
for later review or on-line connection.
<p>
To be more specific in the results the program generates, an advanced search
option allows you to specify which words or phrases must be found to qualify
as a hit.  Conversely, you can also tell the program to ignore documents that
contain certain words or phrases.  This ability to fine-tune your criteria
not only speeds up the search process, but helps you eliminate irrelevant
hits.
<p>
Other goodies include the ability to automatically update and add to your
list of available search engines.  You can also narrow your search to
specific Web or Usenet pages by creating bookmarks and instructing the
program to search only this customized list.  This is especially helpful if
you routinely visit only a select number of sites and wish to search only
those pages for new or updated information.
<p>
The program may seem technical, especially for those new to the on-line
experience, but it is actually extremely easy to use.  Between the printed
manual and excellent on-line help, even novice users will quickly become
experts at pinpointing exactly the information they need.  As an on-line
research tool, EchoSearch is an invaluable resource.
<p>
EchoSearch is available on floppy disk for Windows 95, Windows NT, UNIX and
Macintosh computers.  Product requirements include a modem, Internet or
Intranet connection and Web browser.  Suggested retail price is $49.95, from
Iconovex Corp., (800) 943-0292


</body>
</html>
</DOC>
